deck_excerpt: Most competitive Danger! Dark World Deck 2020
deck_description: The strategy of this deck is simple. Summon a ton of cards while also drawing a ton of cards to dig for your main combo pieces ultimately creating an extremely oppressive board that has only a couple weaknesses. Ideally you want to open a lot of dangers and if you don't your combo can be cut short before you can really get started. That is the inherent weakness of the deck. However, this doesn't happen all that often unless you are having really bad luck with getting your dangers sniped or if your opponent has a lot of hand traps.  The combo pieces you want to dig for are Cyber-stein and plaguespreader. Best case scenerio you get to hold onto your normal summon until you draw cyber-stein but sometimes you will be forced to normal summon something else like armageddon knight or plaguespreader. This is not a big deal because you can summon the cyber-stein off of saryuja's effect. Usually the first monster I summon from the extra deck is Dugares the Timeless. He is easy to summon since there are so many level 4 monsters in the deck. You are almost always going to activate Dugares' first effect, the one that lets you draw 2 and discard for non-cost. This effect is SO good in this deck because the discard will allow you to get a dark world effect if you discard it. If you have a Broww the Hunstman in hand you want to discard that, giving you another draw. After that just summon more dangers until you have 4-5 monsters on field so you can summon Saryuja. If you had 5 monsters on field try to leave a level 4 on field. This will allow you to use saryujas effect to summon plaguespreader from hand (if you drew it or had it already). You can also summon plaguespreader from the GY so don't worry if it ends up there. Once you have Saryuja, a level 4, and Plaguespreader on field, you can go ahead and link Saryuja off for Linkross. You want to summon 3 tokens upon activating linkross effect. This will now allow you to summon Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys and DRAW 4 CARDS off its effect. By now you will probably have at least one beginning of the end or pot of avarice in hand so now it is time to dig for Cyber-Stein. Just keep summoning and drawing cards until you get Cyber-Stein. You can even use Pot of Avarice to put Saryuja back in your extra deck to summon it again to dig for Cyber-Stein thus also granting you a free way to special summon it. Sometimes Cyber-Stein will be towards the bottom of your deck so my rule of thumb is if you have under 10 cards left in your deck it is best to just give up on it and settle for ending on Apollousa Bow of the Goddess, Ravenous Croc, and Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax. If you are able to grab Cyber-Stein, you are going to use its effect to summon Naturia Exterio. This card is very strong as it pretty much lets you negate half the game since it negates both spells and traps and is not once per turn or even once per chain. You just have to make sure that your deck has enough cards to put out enough negates without decking out.  Sorry if this description is confusing but it is kind of hard to make a step by step for this deck since it is all about random drawing and luck. Just test it out and you will eventually understand how to play it efficiently. Also, you can do the draw 4 combo by using Genex Ally Birdman and another monster to summon Crystron Halqifabrax and use its effect to summon Plaguespreader. Now you just need 2 more monsters on board to make Saryuja and then use its effect to summon a level 4.  If you have any questions, please feel free to message me!

deck_excerpt: I think Eldlich is fun. There's still a lot of room for improvement to the deck, even with just the current card pool, and I was excited to see Dogmat
deck_description: Eldlich deck running the Dogmatika engine to hate on the extra deck. A bunch of Rotas let you put El Shaddoll Apkallone into the GY to find the new trap, thus setting up Winda and maybe an extra negate. Forbidden Droplet gives us a spell speed 4 way to help shut down a board full of negates in the high end, and also the benefit of pitching Eldlich cards is pretty high. Eldlich numbers are pretty standard, Extravagance and Magicians' Souls work together to gather card advantage, and no longer requires bricks since Dogmatika monsters are spellcasters.  The extra deck includes a few different packages. There isn't a lot of room for hand traps in the deck, so I'm running packages of 6. Nibiru and Dark Ruler are for combo matchups, though you can also run a combo of Dark Ruler and Forbidden Droplet for Spell Speed 4 negation. Effect Veiler can come in as a generic hand trap, which is generally useful in stopping the opponent's turn, usually alongside Imperm. Lightning Storm, Red Reboot, and Anti-Magic Arrows are for backrow matchups, Eldlich, Altergeist, Guru, to stop their traps, though some Eldlich decks must be treated as combo decks instead. I'd like Cosmic and D.D. Crow for the mirror, but hating on the extra deck and making Winda should help against combo variants, and hopefully the high consistency helps pull ahead against more pure control variants.

deck_excerpt: There's a few new options, so let's try them out. Do your best everyone!
deck_description: The core of the Rock deck has remained the same, but there are some new cards to add to the pool, such as Miracle Rupture and Koa'ki Meiru Supplier. Supplier is a clear upgrade over the other janky generic Earth Rock monsters, but Rupture to send Revival Golem might actually be worse than just running Unexpected Dai, since the Golem isn't a tuna. On the other hand, you can use it as an extender mid-combo, which isn't an option with Unexpected Dai, and you can still build ridiculous boards off of just Gallant Granite.  The other new option is Forbidden Droplet, which gives a spell speed 4 way to get through multiple monster effects at the cost of cards from the hand. Seems like an immediate going second staple in the side deck, and looks main deckable in a lot of circumstances.  The deck still ends on the same(ish) boards, a bunch of lines of interaction plus maybe Abyss Dweller, hopefully I:P with Block Dragon for fun and profit. With Droplet in the Meta I couldn't see Black Luster Soldier - Soldier of Chaos as quite as good an option anymore, but maybe I'm overthinking things, since I'm not sure Dweller fares better against the card.

deck_excerpt: A great and funny Deck for cheesy and interactive plays. Come here if you want to beat Eldlich and Rocks 👀
deck_description:
With the newly added Archetype Dogmatika from the Rise of the Duelist Expansion also comes the new strategy "Dogmatika Invoked". Already being a top tier deck in the OCG it may be worth a try to also try it in the TCG. The Invoked part of the Deck focusses highly around getting out Aleister. You can search him by Magical Meltdown, which also prevents the negation or interruption of your fusion summons. By normal summoning Aleister you can add the Spell Card Invocation. This can be used to fusion summon the Fusion Monsters. First of all, after normal summoning Aleister, the first thing you always do, is to Link summon Almiraj and then Link summon Secure Gardna. Like that you have the needed requirements for Invoked Mechaba, which should be your priority when going first. The Dogmatika part of the Deck focusses more on putting Monsters from your Extra Deck on to the Graveyard to get out your Main Deck Monsters. Ecclesia is the card that can search you any other Dogmatika Card by normal summoning her or by special summoning her when a Monster special summoned from the Extra Deck is on the field. Maximus can be a great card to get 2 monsters from the Extra Deck into your Graveyard, while also forcing your opponent to put 2 in their graveyard. Fleur de Lis is best searched by Ash Dragon in the End Phase, because if you special summon her, she can negate the effects of one of your Opponents Monsters. Punishment can be good for clearing two monsters at once by first of all dumping N'Tss into the graveyard and afterwards with the effect of N'Tss also destroying one of the Opponents Monsters. With Nadir you should always add whatever the situation needs. If you have no Ecclesia I would suggest always getting her, in order for you to search another Dogmatika Card after searching her and therefore getting even more cards into the graveyard. The Last Part of the Deck is the Shaddoll part. It is small but still very important! With any of your Dogmatika cards you can dump Apkallone into your Graveyard activating her effect to search you a Shadoll Schism. If you have then another Dark Monster on your field or your graveyard and the Apkallone still in the Graveyard you can proceed to special summon Winda in your oppponents turn, which prevents him from special summoning more than once. Next up, I will explain why I put the Extra Deck monsters into the Deck like I did:
El Shaddoll Apkallone Like I already said, she is the searcher for Shadoll Schism so you can Summon out Winda
El Shaddoll Winda Winda is very easy to get out in this Deck. You just need a Dogmatika card and one other Dark Monster (what Aleister coincidentally is). Apkallone also forces you to discard a card after activating her effect, so if you draw the Shaddoll Beast you can pitch it, draw a card and also get Winda. So much with only one card!
Elder Entity N'Tss It is just a great card to pitch in your opponents turn with Punishment. Its 2500 ATK gives it a great variety of cards to destroy with Punishment and after that lets you destroy even another card!
Invoked Augoeides Some play this card at 2, but I really do not like that. If necessary you can cycle it with Omega but in my opinion it does not see enough play to be worth the 2 slots. At one it is really good if you want to clear one card of your Opponents field easily and against some decks, they can not comprehend having to destroy the first special summoned card of theirs and cannot play around it. Great floodgate if you play against the right decks. Also really easy to get out later in the game if you have many Fusion Monsters in your Graveyard.
Invoked Mechaba Mechaba is the best Invoked card out their! You have a theoretical omni negate with only 1 card! Aleister into Almiraj into Secure Gardna gives you the needed materials and Aleister even searches you the Invocation. Because often your Mechaba gets Called or you have at the moment no easy way of recycling it, you really want to play 2 of them. Also you can get out 2 of them sometimes and they are only once per copy so you have 2 omni negates at once.
Invoked Purgatrio This is just the card for you to easy board wipe your Opponents monsters and often to OTK him. It is also very easy to get out with just Aleister and Almiraj. Nothing special, just a good card.
Titaniklad the Ash Dragon This card is just there for you to add in your End Phase after pitching him with Nadir, Punishment or Maximus a copy of Fleur de Lis for the great interruption in your Opponents turn.
PSY-Framelord Omega This card is a great way of recycling your already pitched cards. Also you can side in Gamma and Driver so you can sometimes even bring him out.
Wind Pegasus @Ignister Good for interruption, if your Opponent somehow destroys one of your cards but even better in stopping OTK's. When your Opponents tries to, for example, kill you with Borrelsword, he has to first of all kill one of your monsters, which gives you the window to bounce him back to the Extra Deck to live one more turn.
Aleister the Invoker of Madness You do not know how many times I have the situation of being able to summon something with my  Invocation but I have no Aleister. Well that is why I put this card in. Of course you cannot just pitch him with Dogmatika cards and proceed to summon your Invoked cards, but still, I really often had the situation where this guy gave me the Aleister I needed. Also he is a backup when I banished again all of my Aleisters with Pot of Desires lol.
For Handtraps I chose Ash Blossom (3x), Ghost Ogre (2x) and Impermanence (3x) because I think they are the best working in this Deck but also in this format. You can easily swap them out like you want. The same goes for the Side Deck, only Gamma and Driver I would really keep if you want to play Omega, it gives you so much more value. If you want to, you can drop the Omega, Gamma and Driver and instead put Construct into the Main Extra Deck to have another target for Schism. I chose to put her into the Side Deck because in some Match ups she can be really really useless. Dark Ruler can also be swapped for Droplet and Evenly Matched can be swapped for Lightning Storm. The Kaiju comes sometimes really in handy when you want to get rid of negates like Borreload or co. With Nibiru I am thinking of putting in third one, same goes for Called. The Side can easily change depending on the format, but this one really works out for me in this particular format. Last but not least a few warnings and tips when playing with this Deck.
  • Always start with your Invoked cards before using the Dogmatika Cards, they lock you out of the Extra Deck!
  • Do not give up to easily when seeing a big enemy board, the Deck can play through these boards really good!
  • Beware that Punishment locks you out of your Extra Deck the next turn if you activate it in your opponents turn, so you will have to wait with summoning things like Invoked Monsters.
  • The deck is at first glance really easy to play due to the linear combos and easy to understand cards, but it is not as easy as it seems. It is a Deck where you really have to know the format and the other Decks that await you in order to win. Because of the simple and linear cards you have, you really have to be good in every situation. The Deck is not forgiving when it comes to mistakes, every game looks different when playing this Deck. Also their are very cool interactions and cheesy plays possible with the Deck you either have to learn or have to come up with them while playing.
  If you master this Deck I guarantee you a really fun time, due to the different situations every time playing. Right now it is a really strong deck and probably Tier 1 or Tier 2. If you seek for a variation of Dogmatika without the Invoked part I recommend checking out the Dogmatika Eldlich Deck, which I also like playing and which is even stronger than the Dogmatika Invoked variation. If you want to play an Invoked Deck without Dogmatika I would recommend playing Invoked Shaddoll, which is really bad in the current format, but still really fun and capable of winning Locals or even Regionals. Another variation could be Invoked Eldlich which is really good right now, but I would say worse than this Deck and also not fun to play in my opinion or you can play Invoked Mekk-Knight, the oldest meta variation of Invoked, which is pretty okay. When further questions occur or some more tips are needed you can ask in the comment section and I will try my best to help. I wish you a lovely day and take care!

deck_excerpt: Nekroz of Unicore can now be good friends with El Shaddoll Winda. Hand traps can be combo pieces too!
deck_description: Dogmatika and Nekroz actually have some interesting synergies. Notable, the Nekroz monsters are summoned from the hand, not the extra deck, and the deck likes searching by sending Herald of the Arc Light. Rather than try and fit a third engine into the deck, I decided to normal summon hand traps that can go into Almiraj then Secure Gardna, to get a monster from my extra deck onto the field and in the bin. In this sense, the 12 hand traps double as our normal summon. The usual board state you end on is some Dogmatika cards, Nekroz of Unicore, and El Shaddoll Winda on your opponent's turn. Basically you lock them out of the extra deck, and then if they break that you lock them out of summoning. You also have a slew of negation options, with Fleurdelis, Clausolas, and Apkallone (in addition to hand traps and Nekroz cards which are situational hand traps).  The whole plan is normal summon a hand trap, link it into Almiraj, into Secure Gardna, summon Ecclesia, add Maximus, Summon Maximus, send Herald + Apkallone, add a ritual spell/monster, add Shaddoll Schism, discard 1. After that all you need is one Unicore/Clausolas/Brionac/Kaleidoscope and you're making Unicore and Winda.  I have no suggestions for the side deck. Since you need to run hand traps with less than 1000 ATK you can normal summon for the combo, choices for interaction are limited. I put some cards there, but probably the best call is not to side.

deck_excerpt: The only thing that Souten can actually do is just spit out their fusions and be material for Mechaba
deck_description: Normally since this deck has a monster that is a 3k beater Armades that also bounces another monster after it attacks (Kongou, Heavenly General of the Souten), this deck would blind second. However, since this deck can make multiple, somewhat lack luster negations and can be used as material for Mechaba blinding first seems viable. A good starting hand for this deck would be a Souten monster (any is fine, but Koukoku of the Souten Kicks is best for the search for the trap and Yuuhi of the Souten Fists is best for fusion plays) and Souten Calling. Calling can summon up to 5 Tokens which is broken, but you can only fusion summon from the extra deck for the rest of the turn. If you have Koukoku on the field when Calling is activated you can summon 2 Gaiun of the Souten Kicks and have 1 live negate for your opponent's turn. If you have Yuuhi of the Souten Fists, you can make the Armades (Kongou) and a Gaiun with a live negate. If you have Invocation and Aleister, you can then banish an extra token on the field (yes this is legal) or a Souten in the grave to make Mechaba. Koukoku searches your Souten Traps. Two as One is garbage but it searches Souten monsters and it is a Set Rotation target. Meltdown is your other field spell and it searches Aleister. ROTA is actually needed in this deck since there are only 2 unique maindeck Souten monsters and you kind of have to see them in order to get negates. Your interruptions are Ash Blossom, PSY-Framegear Gamma, Souten Exorcism, Souten's Duty (it can copy Exorcism), Gaiun of the Souten Kicks, Invoked Mechaba, and Invoked Augoeides. Going second, Phantazmay and Nibiru are the better hand traps. Impermanence can be sided in for Souten's Duty. Lightning Storm since this deck does not break boards. Kongou and Purgatrio are your damage dealers. Since there are tokens in this deck, which are normal monsters, you could play things like First of the Dragons which is a Towers, but then you would have to play Polymerization since Invocation doesn't banish for the summon unless it's for an Invoked monster. Or you could play Super Polymerization in a going second build with First of the Dragons and other Super Poly targets.

Empowered beyond comprehension by this chaos, the "Fallen of Albaz," an entity of the void, has transformed beyond "Titaniklad" into his final form, "Chaos Emperor, the Dragon of Armageddon!" The end of the world is nigh: will each side come together to summon the ultimate Spellcaster, "Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon," or will the world cease to exist? deck_excerpt: Dark Magician the Dragon Knight counts as Dark Magician. Draw 2+ per turn with the Dark Magician engine combined with the Dogmatika engine, while hati
deck_description: The Dark Magician engine is really really good at doing exactly 1 thing, and that's drawing cards turn after turn. The Dogmatika engine makes Winda, and hates extra decks, and even assists with the Dark Magician thing by throwing Dragon Knight into the bin. You can also make Dragoon or The Dragon Knight, or even The Dark Magicians with Eye of Timaeus, out here rocking Yugi's playbook. Restage with Souls helps gain advantage while searching Right Hand, a Spell Negate that can even get around single copies of Spell Speed 4 spells, gives the deck a little easy negation on an extender, because being real, if you somehow didn't see Souls, you're not doing a lot.  Trying Wonder Wand and Upstart Goblin in the last couple of slots. I really like how Restage feels in combination with, but any card draw helps find souls, which is basically the deck's whole game plan, and I feel light on it. On the other hand, I don't want to run Allure, because the idea is not to banish the Souls.  Cut Eye of Timaeus. The card is great, but the deck was needing more card draw. I'm up to 2 Wonder Wand. This is not the first time I've tried the card, but I was liking it at 1 copy, and I want to see if a second copy helps increase consistency by drawing me Souls after Soul Servant. That also frees up room for Accesscode and the third Winda.  I think the Foolish Burial Goods engine is really good in DM, especially since you can search Right Hand by sending Restage in addition to the Soul Servant and Metalfoes fusion.  I'm down to one Restage. I think I can improve consistency by upping the card draw, and every copy of Foolish Burial Goods can draw me Right Hand if I run 1. I'm also back on 1 Wonder Wand. At 1 in this deck it does help improve consistency a fair bit.  Clara and Rushka should be good enough for a Spellcaster Link 1 until Magistus comes to TCG. I'd probably run Magistus link 1 over Relinquished Anima, and cut Clara and Rushka for something else, maybe another Link 4 or Big Eye.  Magician Girl was just here for the Soul Servant, so I've replaced her with Palladium Oracle Mahad. This might occasionally be another extender with a relevant floating effect, but really, all it has to do to make the slot if be occasionally slightly more useful than DMG.  Turns out DMG being a 1 Tribute monster with 2300-2600 ATK points is more relevant than occasionally special summoning a level 7. Or at the very least it started coming up pretty quickly. I still want to run Eye of Timaeus, but I think I want the Restage / Right Hand more.

deck_name: Rekindling is at 3, Hand Trap Infernoids
deck_excerpt: Mill your Decatrons, activate Rekindling (Soul Charge)! Decatron + Rekindling = 8100.
deck_description: This deck is 60 cards deep because drawing infernoids in your infernoid deck is a bad thing regardless of the build The deck plays 30+ going second cards, 19 of which are hand traps you can use on your opponents turn like Effect Veiler, and some of which can also be used on our own turn like Psy-Framegear Gamma and Infinite Impermanence, and we add another 15 going second cards that can be used to force out negates like Mystic Mine and push through an opponents board, several give you access to your bricks... I mean monsters, such as Void Imagination, Void Vanishment to search Imagination or Void Feast should you actually go first, Void Apocalypse, while a mediocre card it can bait an Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, or set up Rekindling as well being a Void card to be used with Feast, although it will never be searched off of Void Vanishment, although it often is a wonderful top deck milling 1 or more infernoids with its second effect. Because drawing infernoid monsters is so bad I filled the rest of the deck with extenders that go well with Infernoid Decatron like, One for One, Rekindling and Monster Reborn. One normal summoned Decatron plus a reborn card is Crystron Halqifibrax into a 5300 atk Accesscode Talker  plus a summonable Infernoid Attondel for 8100 damage. The play is normal decatron and send whatever (pop a card depending on what was sent), link into Salamangreat Almiraj, reborn decatron and send attondel, link into halqifibrax which summons veiler, then link into Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians link into Accesscode targeting Selene for 5300 atk, then summon Attondel by banishing whatever the first noid sent was and decatron for an additional 2800 atk. This combo is reliant on both players having 3 spells on the field or in the grave but you can always just place Apocalypse, Vanishment, or Lair of Darkness of the field to add additional spells to the count. Another nice play comes off of resolving Feast, you just summon a decatron to zone 2 and 4, and Infernoid Sjette to any other zone. Next you can make 1 decatron and sjette into an Akashic Magician to return the other decatron to hand to be normal summoned regardless of which extra monster zone your opponent may occupy. Then you can potentially co-link Akashic with a Knightmare Phoenix, or a Borrelsword Dragon, Accesscode, or Crusadia Equimax and use her second effect to call whatever card you want in your deck, I usually call Rekindling as its a 3 of and there is a possible benefit of milling Galaxy Cyclone to use on a future turn. The galaxy cyclone also combos with mine and feast, you can activate cyclone in grave to turn off your own mine then chain feast while your opponent cannot respond with monster effects. You can also play around mine with feast and imagiantion if your opponent has two or more monster and one was from the extra deck. You can summon Infernoid Tierra, and use it to mill 2 Elder Entity N'tss and something else. You can then use N'tss to pop mine and chain feast to dodge Ash.

deck_excerpt: Fossil Fusion is searchable by Neos Fusion by sending Weathering Soldier. With Mathematician, we will have 11 Fossil Fusion (is a one-card Halq too, y
deck_description: Self explanatory, it is one-card Halq + billion Fossil Fusion searchers. Neos Fusion summons Brave Neos by sending Weathering Soldier and the Neos in GY is a perfect fodder for Skull King cus it's lv7, we're playing 2 Neos as follow-up with Rainbow Neos cus it's so powerful. Mathematician and Foolish Burial can either send Jet Synchron or Weathering for Fossil Fusion (if sending Weathering, make sure we have access to Halq by having Tuning/Quickdraw Synchron).  The fossil lineup: 2 Weathering (just in case it's drawn, cus it cant activate from cost, ex. Jet Synchron), 3 Miracle Rupture (searcher and plus if have Fossil Fusion already), 2 Fossil Fusion (2 cus it's dead if drawn, no rock in GY, playing 2 as followup too), 1 Time Stream (searchable, ss Fossil monster from GY).  Tuning/Synchron package is perfect for this deck as Tuning can send Weathering/Fossil card if lucky, Jet is so powerful, and Quickdraw helps Mathematician for Fossil play. The rest is just combo pieces and staple (Nibiru helps alot too, either as Crossout target or Fossil Fusion material).  Pros: Super consistent combo, Fossil followup is self-recurring, can OTK going second.  Cons: Boring Halq deck.  Cards to think of: Scrap Recycler (another one-card Halq, but can't send Weathering), Gallant Granite/Block Dragon/Adaman Researcher (broken great extenders, but we need to jump several hoops to make it).

deck_excerpt: If you want a deck-skeleton of the new Dogmatika Invoked deck, be my guest and read the article, how YOU can beat the meta with the strategies of the
deck_description:
So where do i begin... probably with
  • The Invoked engine consists of 10 spots dedicated in the main deck and 6 in the extra, this should be the standard ratio you would see in a lot of invoked decklists, the only thing that maybe weird is the 3rd invocation in a non-desires build, the theory behind that one was that you want to open with invocation every game in case your Aleister the Invoker gets stopped.
  • The Dogmatika engine has unlike the Invoked engine only 9 cards but all of them are very good. We play 3 ecclesia which is the stratos of the archetype, then we play 1 of Maximus and Fleur de lis, both only benefit you if you search them and don't help on their own so multiple would only make your hands worse you can maybe decide to play more than 1 Maximus but i won't recommend it because you only run a limited amount of targets, Fleur de lis is nice to OTK your opponent with only Dogmatika cards. As the only 'Dogmatika' spell we play the Nadir Servant which is the E-Emergency call or the Reinforcement of the Army of the deck, the only downside to it is it doesn't have  Dogmatika in the name so it's not searchable by Ecclesia. As only Trap of the deck we play Dogmatika Punishment it's just an additional target for Ecclesia and can help you out problem monsters. In the Extra Deck we only play Titaniklad as a 'real' dogmatika card.
  • The Shaddoll package has only 3 spots in the main and extra they can be searched by dumping Apkalone with your dogmatika cards. We play 1 Beast and 1 Dragon in addition to the Schism in case we already drew it. Beast helps us dig deeper into the deck and to see more handtraps, Dragon helps us against problem spells/traps like Rivalry of Warlords or Gozen Match.
  • The Hand Traps/other cards we play about 15 Hantraps in the Main Deck and 3 Forbidden Droplet. For Hand Traps we play 3x Gamma + 1x Driver because it is actually the best Hand Trap this format, it can stop a variety of monster effects with the cost of running one brick in your deck. We also play 3 Nibiru so we can have a better chance against all the Combo Decks in the meta. 3 Ash Blossom are in here just because it is the best against every matchup. Ghost ogre is the only Handtrap we are running at 2 just because it has a limited usage in most matchups and in the matchups it's good against it can limit your opponent in his/her plays. 3 Infinite Impermanence is just the best hand trap you can have going second, in a format full of decks that turbo out true king of all calamities or utopic zexal it and gamma can help you beat those decks. 3 Droplets are essentially the same as impermanence but also can be used if you control another card on the field but only on your first turn.
  • The Extra Deck: We play 2 Mechaba with the reasoning you only need 1 but in the mirror you can send cyber dragon nova off the opponents maximus effect to summon the 2nd, the 1 Augoeides comes up in the grind game when you have to remove monsters  from the field. Purgatrio is only in there to OTK your opponent. We play 1 of each Construct, Winda and Apkalone reasoning being you only need 1 of each for your 1 combo going first. As targets for Nadir/Maximus/Punishment we play 1 Fossil Warrior Skull Knight, 1 N'tss 1 Omega 1 Cyber Dragon Nova and 1 Titaniklad. Skull Knight and N'tss do similar where they both destroy cards on the field, the difference being that skull knight is an ignition effect that only can destroy monsters by banishing itself from the gy, but N'tss being a trigger effect that immediately after resolution is applied. I play 1 Anaconda Verte for the side decked super polymerization 2 Semi Invoked cards are Salamangreat Almiraj and Secure Gardna which turn 1 Aleister into a mechaba.
  • The Side Deck is built with side pattern:
    Side Deck
    Main Deck
    Matchups/Reasoning
    1x Pankratops + 3x Cosmic Cyclone + 3x Twin Twisters
    1x Driver + 3 Gamma +3 Nibiru
    You side these in a control  matchup going 1st & 2nd like subterror or altergeist just because gamma and Nibiru don't do anything in those Matchups
    1x Artifact Scythe + 2x Sanctum + 1x Trap Trick
    1x Driver + 3x Gamma
    This is your side plan for going first against a Combo/ Extra Deck-heavy Deck
    1x Starving venom/Dragon knight draco equiste + 2x Super Poly +1x Pankratops
    1x Nova +1x Shaddoll Beast 1x Shaddoll Dragon+1x Schism
    You side these in a relevant matchup going second.
  •  A Combo: So the most simple 2 card combo is a way to aleister the invoker and nadir servant. So you start off by doing the standard Invoked stuff with normal summoning aleister adding invocation linking aleister away for almiraj linking almiraj away into secure gardna and activating invocation banishing secure gardna on field and aleister in gy to summon invoked mechaba from the extra deck then you use invocation effect to shuffle it back and adding aleister from the banish pile to the hand. After that you activate nadir servant to send apkalone and adding maximus. apkalone triggers adding schism and discarding it again. you summon maximus by banishing apkalone from the gy. then you use the effect of maximus sending titaniklad and el shaddoll construct el shaddoll construct triggers adding back the schism and then you set the schism go into end phase activating tianiklad summoning ecclesia and ecclesia adds fleur de lis.on your opponents turn you have 1 Mechaba negate, 1 Winda and 1 Fleur delis negate.

deck_excerpt: Topple the meta with a deck full of answers
deck_description: Numeron got you down? Sick of Dogmatika already? Got the Adamancipator blues? Well good news, there's a deck for you! Why play Salamangreat in this meta? Salamangreat can naturally run a large number of handtraps and removal, meaning it can be tailored to fight whatever is popular at the moment. While not the best deck, Salamangreat can be built to combat many decks. Salamangreat can also shut down most rogue decks with ease. Card Choices: 2 Pot of Desires: 3 bricks too often, and there's a good number of cards in this deck that you don't want to banish. Salamangreat Fowl: Probably the most contentious spot. This can be replaced with a Jack Jaguar, Lady Debug, or a trap; however, the extender can be useful in setting up early boards. Gravedigger's Trap Hole/Traptrix Rafflesia: Losing to Nibiru sucks, especially if you just get OTK'd the following turn. Can also be used to stop other hand traps, like Ghost Ogre and Ash Blossom (although if you've made Rafflesia, they've probably already tried to handtrap you) Ghost Ogre vs. Nibiru: Nibiru used to be the maindeck anti-combo tech of choice, but many decks like Adamancipator can stop Nibiru, and decks like Eldlich, Dogmatika, and Numeron simply don't care if you have Nibiru. We still run it in the side, but Ghost Ogre stops more threats among the top meta decks. It shuts down Numeron especially hard. D. D. Crow: This can be replaced with Phantazmay or Nibiru if you don't find yourself playing against much Eldlich. However, with Invoked Dogmatika running around, shutting off your opponents from making Invoked plays can be clutch. 2 Lady Debug/2 Flame Bufferlo: You can play 3/1 Debug/Bufferlo if you want, but often times I find that having 6 searches is unnecessary, and Bufferlo can draw into traps or extenders. Also, with Parallel eXceed, you have more cyberse monsters to pitch to Bufferlo, if you find you don't need the eXceed. 3 Cosmic Cyclone: You really, really don't want to lose to Numeron. There's a lot of it these days, so doubling up on ways to out it is good. You can replace these with other hand traps if you aren't facing a lot of Numeron 2 Infinite Impermanence: You can run 3, cutting a Cyclone, Crow, Gravedigger's, or Fowl, but I find that two suffices with all the other hand traps and answers you have. Side Deck: 3 Sphere Mode: Just another way to deal with Adamancipator and Combo Eldlich. This spot can be modified to fit your needs. 3 Dark Ruler No More: See Sphere Mode 3 Evenly Matched: See Dark Ruler No More 2 Phantazmay/1 D. D. Crow: Play whatever you want here. These slots are somewhat extraneous. How to play:  Going first: Build a board and try to set up some backrow. Watch out for Nibiru. Going second: Accescode Talker and OTK. Any Salamangreat monster and Parallel eXceed is a 5300 ATK Accescode + 3 pops that can attack twice. Not much can beat it.

deck_excerpt: OTK combo with Sieger + Rampage + (optional) Infinity.
deck_description: The ultimate deck combo is basically summoning, Sieger, Infinity and Rampage Dragon. With Rampage and Sieger you have your OTK but with an extra Infinity there isn’t much your opponent can do to stop it.  First determine how many cyber dragons you can get out on the field, if you don’t have a full set to make Sieger, Infinity and Rampage, ditch Infinity if you want to go for the OTK or play save with Infinity and Sieger with some backrow. If you can summon enough you can create Infinity easily with Galaxy soldier or with a Cyber Dragon Vier and Cyber Dragon Drei combo. When you do create him don’t forget to use Nova's effect to get back a Cyber Dragon from your grave if you managed to get one there (can be done by linking Sieger first). After you got your Infinity you can go ahead and create Rampage, since you are now able to negate any one effect, they throw at you. Create Rampage with overload fusion, or Cyberload fusion which is searchable for Cyber Dragon Core, or you can use the new Cyber Pharos card to do it. With that you can pretty much delete your opponent’s backrow and use Rampage his effect to get 3 attacks, buff him with Sieger effect in combat phase and you can attack 3x with a 4200-attack monster. That is often game if you play your cards right.  Quick side note: if you are planning on summoning Infinity do it early because this prevents an unwanted Nibiru being summoned, because then you can simply negate it.  This deck gives you the possibility to get yourself out of the toughest spots and creates its most powerful monsters in many different ways.

deck_name: Go 2nd Gren Maju OTK with Dangers & Castle of Stromberg
deck_excerpt: Go 2nd Gren Maju OTK deck with Dangers and Castle of Stromberg. Offers good cycling and removal with cards like Trade-In, Desires, Lightning Storm, et
deck_description: A go 2nd Gren Maju deck. Overall this deck offers a good amount of cycling and removal, allowing you to get to your key cards and clear the field for a quick OTK. It's very easy to banish 30+ cards in one turn and get a Gren Maju with 10 000+ ATK.  You don't always draw Gren Maju and there's no reliable way to search it, however it's still possible to OTK without it. Most of the time you can OTK on the 2nd turn. This deck doesn't do well against boards with lots of negates or monsters immuned to targeting/destruction, so I'd say it's just a casual deck for fun.  Core of the deck : Gren Maju and Pot of Desires. Don't play these at less than 3.   Hand traps are here to slow your opponent going first, feel free to swap them for other hand traps if you don't like these ones.  Lvl 8 Danger cards combined with Trade-In allow for deck cycling and removal. Bigfoot needs to be at 3 but you can play Thunderbird at 2.  Eater of Millions and Orochi help to banish cards and give access to more removal. Always play them at 3.  Castle of Stromberg offers banishing although slower than the other cards and gives easy access to Hexe Trude for extra removal. Hexe Trude is also a target for Trade-In. You can change the ratios for Glife and Hexe Trude if you want.  A single Kaiju, because it's always good removal and it's a target for Trade-In. Feel free to swap it for something else.  Lightning Storm is an excellent go 2nd card, allowing you to clear the board or backrow if you're playing against a backrow heavy deck. Just be careful not to use Orochi on your opponent's turn or you won't be able to use Lightning Storm. Raigeki is an "extra copy" of Lightning Storm.  Extra Deck is filled with Rank 8s as it's easy to go into them. You don't really use it going 2nd since you'll most likely banish it, but going first you can easily put Hope Harbinger or Seven Sins on board for negation or protection. I didn't put much thoughts into it since it's entirely banished most of the time, so you could tinker with it to see what works best.  I don't play Extravagence or Duality because their restrictions restrain the Deck too much. You could play Allure but it's kinda bricky.  I don't play Dark Ruler No More & Evenly Matched because this deck needs the Battle Phase. You could try a Kaiju engine with Interrupted Slumber for more field removal if you are not satisfied with Raigeki + Lightning Storm. Necroface is also an option offering great recycling.

deck_excerpt: A different, non-meta way to play a meta combo
deck_description: Hello again! This is a highly experimental deck, but it makes Halqifibrax surprisingly consistently. Let's talk about the card choices. MONSTERS 1x Infernity Archfiend - The iconic Infernity card. Unfortunately at 1, and with Lavalval Chain being banned, this card is surprisingly hard to special summon. However, when you do, you get a search, provided you have no cards in hand. 3x Infernity Wildcat - Part of the new support from Phantom Rage! You can discard an Infernity to special this card from the hand, which allows you to both get a tuner on the field without using your normal and empty your hand. You really want to see this in your opening. 3x Infernity Conjuror - Also part of the new support, can special summon itself from the grave with an empty hand. Mostly used as a non-tuner body. 3x Infernity Necromancer - Allows you to special an Infernity from the grave with an empty hand. This can be used to trigger Archfiend, or grab a tuner from the grave for your main combo. 2x Infernity Mirage - Can tribute itself to special summon 2 Infernity monsters from the grave with an empty hand. Great for either starting your combo, or grabbing more resources in the mid-late game. 1x Armageddon Knight - We have so many monsters we want to dump into the grave, so this card is pretty self explanitory. 5x Danger Monsters - The Danger engine is really useful in this deck. The discard effect helps in emptying the hand, and maybe grabbing some extra cards along the way. Worst case scenario, all of them are dark, making them Allure targets. 1x O-lion, 1x Deskbot 001 - Combo pieces. Deskbot isn't the worst thing to draw, since Halq can summon from the hand, but drawing O-lion means you're going to be playing a slow game. SPELL/TRAP 3x Infernity Paranoia - More new support! Allows you to tribute a dark to special an Infernity of the same level from your deck. Also allows you to add back Infernity monsters from the grave on later turns. Amazing with Conjuror or Wildcat in hand, both giving a Halq summon. Since the tributed monster doesn't have to be an Infernity, you can also tribute a Danger monster for either another level 3 or to set up an Archfiend for later. 3x Allure of Darkness - Draw power. Also allows you to empty your hand. 1x One for One - Gives you either Mirage for summons, or a Deskbot for an emergency tuner. 3x Transmodify - Probably the most controversial card in the deck in my opinion, especially since we really only run 1 target for it. The Archfiend summon is SUPER important, however, and I feel like this adds a little bit of consistency to your searches. 1x Foolish Burial, Monster Reborn, Infernity Launcher - We like the grave One thing to point out about the spell lineup is we don't play any quick plays, meaning all of these can be set before you use them to empty your hand. Remember this, it comes up often! 3x Infernity Suppression - With an empty hand, this stops monster effects! Can be used aggressively on your opponents turn to stop effects, or more commonly, to stop hand traps on your own turn. As good as it is, it only works with an Infernity on the field, which can make it dead sometimes. 3x Infernity Barrier - Stops everything but summons. Same as above, but the negation is incredibly good, it feels wrong not to run this at 3. 1x Infernity Break - Not great removal, but removal nonetheless. EXTRA 1x Halqifibrax, 1x Linkross, 1x Metal Marcher, 1x Barricadeborg Blocker, 1x Auroradon, 1x Herald, 1x Borreload Savage - Combo Pieces. I'll link the main combo below! 1x Omega - For the rare times we can make an 8 and can't use Borreload Savage 1x Goyo, 1x Coral Dragon, 1x Infernity Hell Archfiend, 1x Desert Locusts - Level 6 Synchros are braindead to make in this deck, with both Coral Dragon and Desert Locusts being Halq targets on your opponents turn. 1x Accesscode, 1x Knightmare Unicore, 1x Knightmare Phoenix - General links, to be honest I don't go into these often but they're there if you need them.   MAIN COMBO In case you don't know the main Halq combo, this is what I do. Link into Halqifibrax > Special Deskbot > Link into Linkross > Synchro for Metal Marcher > Special Deskbot > Deskbot and Linkross into Barricadeborg > Link into Auroradon > Special Deskbot from grave > Auroradon special O-lion from deck > Synchro into Borrelsavage > Synchro into Arc Light   Like I said, this deck is super experimental, but hopefully you enjoy it as much as I have!

deck_excerpt: The new deck that will be in Phantom Rage
deck_description: This deck goes first to set up a pseudo Herald of the Arc Light (banish cards sent to the grave) and at most 3 other forms of disruptions. You can think of this deck as Salamangreat Gazelle the deck since each card in the archetype Special Summons itself in someway. You really want your starting hand to have a lot of extenders so you can go into your synchro and xyz plays. If you want to do link plays, you have to do it before using any of the Gazelle effects. The starters you want to see are Datascape Rabbit - Tutu and any way to get Datascape Gate - Qinglong into the grave other than Datascape Servant - Laolao. Rabbit is your normal summon and an extender from grave. Laolao summons a Datascape from grave so you don't want to summon it at this point since you won't have any in the grave. Qinglong banishes itself to search a Datascape monster and you should really search Laolao at this point so you can special summon the Datascape that you discarded from Qinglong. From there, your first priority should be making interruptions on your opponent's turn like Number 3: Cicada King or Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys. The last interruption you want to make is Datascape Fox - Xianxian since its Herald eff is for your cards too. If you know that your opponent runs Infinite Impermanence you can make Naturia Barkion with things like Psychic Wheeleder, Psychic Tracker, and Gallis the Star Beast (these also can act as your extenders). Every card in this deck is an extender (YEP CRACKED). Desires since we NEED to see those extenders. Interruptions you can make for your opponent's turn are Datascape Fox - Xianxian, Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys, Naturia Barkion, Adamancipator Risen Raptite, Hyper Psychic Riser (in dire situations or you bricked), Desert Locusts (if you made Halqifibrax), VFD, Number 3: Cicada King, Datascape Phoenix - Fengfeng (for recovery), and Datascape Shell - Jiajia. Datascape Gate - Zhuque is also a negation. Since we are going first, we are trying to make as many interruptions as possible and since every card in this deck can be Ashed we are playing Called by the Grave. Also of course we are playing Barkion for Impermanence. Going second, we can side in things like Ghost Ogre, Nibiru, Tactics Talent, Dark Ruler No More, and Infinite Impermanence. Going second, Hyper Psychic Riser is like Dark Ruler on legs, but don't use it for that since it affects you too. You can also go into the Aussa link to get value off your opponent's grave. I don't advise playing the Wynn link since there are very few decks that will probably use wind monsters. The most cracked card in this deck is Datascape Capital - Jiulong since it can summon 4 Extra Deck Datascapes, but you need to control 4 Datascape Gate cards. Unless we see more support for this deck by which I mean more Gate cards, I don't see people trying to resolve this effect.

deck_excerpt: Paleozoic Frogs aren't dead YET!   (Also, Tsuyu Asui is best girl, and My Hero Academia is best anime!)
deck_description: This is a Paleozoic Frog deck that uses the Trap Card, Warning Point. Warning Point triggers when a monster is Summoned, and prevents that monster from attacking or being used as material for a Fusion/Synchro/Xyz/Link Summon, and also negates that monster's effects for the turn. I mainly got the idea to use this in Frogs because that deck is chockful of Normal Traps. Not to mention that it can be searched out by Lilith, Lady of Lament and Trap Trick.     I decided to name this deck "Kero!", the Japanese onomatopoeia for a frog croaking. In My Hero Academia--or "Boku No Hero Academia" for you filthy weebs--Tsuyu Asui has a habit of saying "Kero." In the English dub, that sound is replaced with her saying "Ribbit!"     This deck functions just like a normal Paleo Frog would, so you absolutely NEED to go first! The Side Deck also contains some floodgates, Anti-Spell Fragrance, and Solemn Judgment, just in case your opponent is playing this deck's worst nightmare: Lightning Storm. Now that you know how this deck works, make sure to GO BEYOND, PLUS ULTRA!!

deck_excerpt: Blackwing, Red eyes dragun, Xyz, Synchro
deck_description: Here's one of my favorite deck ever, the blackwing! Waiting for the new "Raiders" and phantom knights support (ocg now), I realized this build. Very fast and versatile with many skilled combos. The Main one is this by having a Simoon, another blackwing and Blizzard the far north/ or black whirlwind in order to take one more blackwing when you normal.  1. Attivate Simoon's effect. Place whirlwind and add Auster. Normal summon Auster and call back the banished monster by Simoon's effect and add Harmattan for whirlwind's effect (if you preaviously had a whirlwind in the hand, take Blizzard too).  2. Special summon Harmattan without activating its effect on the field and Synchro summon Nothung in the Extra zone. Normal summon Blizzard for Nothung's effect, special summon Harmattan from the GY and add Oroshi the squall from your deck because of black whirlwind. Now attivate Harmattan's effect targeting Blizzard to make it become lv4, special summon oroshi from your hand.  Now you should have:  Simoon, Nothung in the extra zone, Blizzard the far north, the blackwing special summoned by Auster and Oroshi for the monsters and At least 1 Black Whirlwind in the spell/trap card zone.  3. Now, use Nothung and Oroshi to summon Blackwing Tamer Hawk Joe on the field (Absolutely not in the extra monster zone), the use its effect to call Nothung back and then, use Nothung and the blackwing preaviously special summoned by Auster to link summon Raidraptor-Wise strix. Use wise strix's effect to special summon Zephyros from the deck. Then, xyz summon Raidraptor- Force strix by using Zephyros and the lv4 Harmattan as material.  4. Use force strix's effect to add Raiders' Wing to your hand.  Special summon it by detaching Zephyros from Force strix and then, call back Zephiros by returning black whirlwind to your hand (avoiding so the Simoon effect in the end phase). Then, use Zephyros and Raider's wing to special summon another force strix and its effect by detaching Raiders wing to add another lv 4 winged beast monster from you deck (generally Bora or Kris). Then, wise strix's second effect activates and set from you deck to your field the Rank up magic- phantom knight's force.  At this point you should have on the field:  Simoon, Blizzard, Wise strix (in the EMZ), 2 Force strix (one of them without xyz materials) and the set Rank up magic quick spell (you won't activate it this turn).  5. Use Wise Strix and the force strix without materials to link summon Verte Anaconda in the Extra monster zone. Then, use Blizzard and Simoon to synchro summon Borrel Savage Dragon targeting wise strix in the GY to equip him.  6. Finally, use Verte anaconda's effect to send the Red Eyes Fusion spell from you deck to the GY (as Wells as Dark magician and Red eyes Black dragon) ti special summon Dragun of Red Eyes.  7. In the opponent's draw phase, use the set rank up magic on your force strix, remote 6 dark monster from the GY and overlap xyz summon Raidraptor- Ultimate Falcon.     And this was the dark combos starting by Simoon. Eventuali, you can also start different the and set up the rank up soul shave force instead of the quick one to use it on you turn to special summon Cyber dragon infinity. Then, after you summon red eyes dragun, use the first effect of Cyber Dragon infinity to absorb the verte anaconda (considering that you should have At this point, 1800 Lp because of both the effect of soul shave force plus verte anaconda which can't be' used first the rank up It you want summon Infinity too).  I just considered the Basic combo. In reality, you could have much more than this.  Enjoy!

deck_excerpt: Galaxy-Eyes Are Amazing and This Deck is Actually in the TCG
deck_description: I started to play galaxy photon, a couple of weeks ago and I even did a deck profile on it, but I kept on losing to the meta. I also noticed that galaxy photon was pretty useless without afterglow dragon. This deck does not have galaxy eyes afterglow because it is not released in the TCG sadly. I started to put in a lot of other engines together into this deck and had to watch a lot of Yu-Gi-Oh Videos and combos and I got this deck. Some people might ask how to play this deck and how it is even close to a combo/meta deck. Dogmatika The reason why I played Dogmatika was because it was just a light engine that stopped everything. And it was a light engine. That's useful to Galaxy Soldier that was almost the only reason why I decided to play it. I unfortunately won't be playing the invoked engine along with it. deck_excerpt: Eldlich ft. a small package of Prank-Kids, utilizing the upcoming Prank-Kids Link-1
deck_description: The goal of the deck is to do the usual Eldlich grind strategy while also setting up a double monster wipe off of Battle Butler. Ideally you want to go first as this deck struggles pretty hard to break established boards, so your side deck should generally focus more on solving this problem if the many hand traps prove insufficient. You can get to a Butler off of any Prank-Kid, by doing as follows: - Normal summon any Prank-kid, link into Meow-Meow (which summons a different Prank-Kid from the hand/deck) - Link the Meow-Meow and that Prank-Kid into Bow-Wow-Bark (which summons a different kid) - Link the Bow-Wow-Bark and that Prank-Kid into Dodo-Doodle-Doo, using its effect to search out Prank-Kids Pandemonium (and summoning a different Prank-kid from the deck which MUST be either Fansies, Dropsies or Lampsies) -Activate Dodo-Doodle-Doo, adding back the other two materials for Battle Butler from your GY to your hand -At this point, with some combination of Fansies, Dropsies and Lampsies in your hand/on your field, activate Pandemonium to fuse all 3 into Battle Butler (which locks you into Prank-Kids for the rest of the turn, so you'll want to either summon your Eldlich the Golden Lord using his own effect first, or wait until your opponent's turn to summon him using Eldlixer of Scarlet Sanguine/White Destiny) *Side note: when you mill a card for Fansies' effect, just send a copy of Prank-Kids Place since you won't be needing it at that point. Furthermore, make sure to not banish any Prank-Kids from your hand for Rocksies' effect as you need all 3 other Prank-Kids in play to make the Battle Butler. Technically you can do this combo without Rocksies (instead just going Kid -> Meow-Meow + Kid -> Dodo + Kid -> Dodo effect to add back kids -> Pandemonium for Butler), but using Rocksies allows you to fix a dead handtrap in your hand (like Nibiru) and sets up an additional attribute in the GY for Accesscode Talker later. Otherwise, this deck works just like your typical Eldlich affair, with Crystron Halqifibrax + Selene to get an easy Accesscode Talker turn 3/4 using Effect Veiler. The Extra Deck is extremely flexible beyond the Halq/Selene/Accesscode package and the Prank-Kids cards, so really you can run whatever you want (I opted here for several links to link away already-used Conquistadors and Huaqueros, but really you could run whatever you want). Furthermore, the Side Deck should obviously be tailored to fit your own personal preferences/needs. Is this particular combination of decks any better than the countless other Eldlich mashups (Invoked, Dogmatika, etc.)? Probably not, as Prank-Kids are notoriously fragile and are countered by just about every hand trap currently played. That being said, the double Battle Butler wipe is certainly funny to pull off and can set you up for an easy grind/OTK later as your opponent struggles to get enough field presence to power through your Eldlich cards.

deck_excerpt: A deck featuring the "Battleguards", which tries to make some plays with Level 5 Warrior monsters.
deck_description:
This is my "Battleguard" deck. The "Battleguards" are not close to being a popular or even known deck type, but I tried to make something out of it to the best of my ability.

Obviously, the deck needs three copies of both "Swamp Battleguard" and "Lava Battleguard", since they are what gives the deck its name. On their own, they are rather uninteresting and even in pairs they only boost their stats by a small margin, but with "Feast of the Wild LV5", we can Special summon the duo for further Xyz and Link summons, or to go into their "boss monster" in form of "Battleguard King".

The "Star" series of cards provides some further summoning material, with "Tenma the Sky Star" being Normal summonable without tribute while you control an Earth monster (a requirement that the "Battleguards" can provide), while "Hayate the Earth Star" can enter the field via Normal Summon when a Light monster is present. They also bring their friends with the other Attribute with them when summoned, allowing for some swarming and the summon of "Kaiki the Unity Star", who then can summon the Fusion monster "Idaten the Conqueror Star" for a surprisingly helpful beater with an in-built search effect.

To make summoning some Level 5 monsters a little easier, I included both "Overlay Booster" and "Super Quantum Red Layer" into the mix, both sporting a Special summon effect and being overall useful for the strategy.

In the backrow you will find "Monster Reborn" for easy revival, "United We Stand" as a ghetto OTK option, "Raigeki" for board clear, "Pot of Desires" for draw power (we play enough copies of everything, so the banish effect is pretty much irrelevant), "The Monarchs Stormforth" as both removal and tribute summon option if needed and "Instant Fusion" to gain access to either "Invoked Raidjin" if you need an added effect on a Level 5 Warrior monster or "Giltia the D. Knight" if you could start a summon chain with "Hayate the Earth Star".

The Traps consist of "Lost Wind", which stops the opposing effect monsters while lowering their ATK to beatable levels, "Wall of Disruption" as a better version of "Mirror Force" in this deck since any damage you can inflict helps in the long run, "Crackdown" to steal the opposing defenses, "Battleguard Howling" for further damage and board control and a "Call of the Haunted" in case you need to revive another monster.

The Extra Deck is mainly Rank 5 Xyz monsters with useful effects, some Links to have certain options available, the "Instant Fusion" targets as well as "Idaten the Conqueror Star" and "Shura the Combat Star" for the "Kaiki the Unity Star" summon.

The deck is nowhere near consistent. In fact, it is very bricky and can have some serious issues in certain situations, but that is exactly why I listed it as a Casual deck. If you want the challenge of working with "Battleguards" though, this deck can be the way to go. I even made an archetype analysis for the "Battleguards" (as well as some other archetypes), which you can find here: https://cubiccreativity.wordpress.com/2020/08/20/archetype-analysis-battleguard/

deck_excerpt: Your typical Eldlichnumerondogmatikashaddollinvoked deck, splashable in milk and rich in vitamin S0!
deck_description: This was to be an experiment to combine all the most annoying overplayed metadecks, but Adamancipator wouldn't mix! This combines Eldlich, Numeron, Shaddoll, Invoked and Dogmatika to ensure your opening hand with make your YGOPRO opponent roll their eyes from seeing the same garbage they always fight.   Strategy: Um, really? Ok. The deck has many ways to get Numeron Network, but only one Numeron Calling. This is because I've never had a duel where I could have one if I had another, it was either doomed from the get-go or win more. Add more if you feel you need them, the Extra deck is already cluttered as is. Go for the likely to be banned ZEXAL or if the opponent will counter this, Number C1: Numeron Chaos Gate Sunya or Infinitrack Fortress Megaclops, I prefer it over Avramax, but he's in the extra deck if you need to swap. If you don't get Numeron Network early on, aim for Invoked Mechaba or El Shaddoll Winda as they can control games by themselves. Eldlich, Dogmatika, and Invoked easily cycle themselves as long as you draw their recycler card (For Eldlich, just send a trap to the graveyard) Shaddoll are kind of the weak link sadly, as there's only so much space. You can search out Shaddoll Schism with El Shaddoll Apkallone trough fusion, or sending to the graveyard with Dogmatika abilities, if you can get off a fusion with it, it's pretty effective against Light/Dark decks. Finally use Shapesnatch for a full board and hand wipe.

deck_description: You can search gamma for the synchron combo and sync it with the zeta in the same turn, sending it through the maxymus or disciple of nadir effect

Primarily functions as a beatdown due to most of the link monsters' effects that let them gain ATK.  Summon a Crusadia monster. Use it to link summon Magius. Special summon another Crusadia monster to Magius' zone by it's own effect. Activate Magius' effect to add another Crusadia to your hand. Link summon a LINK-2 monster. Summon the new Crusadia monster by it's own effect. You may now active activate additional effects if you chose Spatha or Regulex. Link summon again for either Equimax or Topologic Trisbeana. If you find yourself too vulnerable with only Equimax. Consider using I:P Masquerna as it's material to protect it from effects, or use Regulex to get Crusadia Power to protect it. You can also get Crusadia Revival to boost it's ATK, make it less vulnerable in battle. If you think you can win a battle, you can use Crusadia Testament instead to draw cards and hopefully get a Crusadia monster to boost Equimax's ATK.  Kaiju Monsters can be used to take advantage of Equmax's or Regulex's Up-pointing arrow.  If you're looking for a more defensive play, Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax is a great candidate. Your opponent can only attack it, and it gains ATK equal to that of a special summoned monster it's battling. Not to mention that fact that your opponent can't can't target it with card effect, making this much more difficult.     Seriously though these new backgrounds are awesome!

Dogmatika comes into a very hostile meta with a bang. Finding a natural home alongside the Invoked engine, Invoked Dogmatika has quickly become a competitor in todays meta. However, there is some uncertainty surrounding this deck. While though the deck's potential is high, its consistency tends to be an issue in long tournament settings, and has a tendency to produce awkward hands and scenarios, that can leave it outpaced in a world filled with, "Halqross," combo decks. That being said, in the hands of an experienced player, Invoked Dogmatika is, without a doubt, one of the best decks in the current meta. I would rate it as a Tier 2 deck.

deck_excerpt: Overview over Phantasm Spiral and a few card choices.
deck_description: This particular deck version works decently well vs Blue Eyes as Fire Formation - Tenki paired with Phantasm Spiral Grip allows you to go kill regular Blue Eyes in Defense Position aswell as the Dragon that banishes Spells/Traps. The plan with this Deck is very simple, as always: Get your Field Spell up and prevent the Opponent from doing anything about it. Some of the "one of" cards in this deck might seem off, but both Wave and Power are searchable and in this particular match-up not the cards you really need, but still have their value. Powers effects are both situationally useful, getting a copy of an Equip Spell back is huge and lowering Attack/Defense can sometimes be make or break in this particular match-up. Usually you want more than 1 Power in the Deck, but Blue Eyes sadly doesnt really too heavily on Effect Monsters so ultimately its best at 1. Wave on the other Hand is usually not good enough to be ran, but since Phantasm Spiral likes long Duels more than most other Decks this card can help you get there by summoning a Dragon of your own no matter what while discarding one of your opponents Hand cards. I'm personally running Beast-Warrios over Megalo here, only because the 100 extra Attack from Tenki is useful vs Blue Eyes and because Blue Eyes banishes our Field Spell so Sea Stealth Attack isnt as good sadly :(   Enough of that. A few words to every card in this Deck (including Extra Deck, which are cards that are good in general for this Deck) Phantasm Spiral Dragon: Our "Boss" Monster, biggest Hitter, we can summon them from Deck/GY/Hand with the equip Spells, never run 3, maybe run 2, most of the time 1 will be enough. A lot of decks don't run him, I like him though. Gene-Warped Warwolf: 4 Star Normal with 2000 ATK, thats all we want. Beast-Warrior so he works with Tenki Dragoons of Draconia: 4 Star Normal. Very rarely useful for its Pendulum Spell Effect, mostly there to not run out of Steam, also Beast-Warrior for Tenki Ash-Blossom: Probably the best Handtrap Fire Formation - Tenki: Searches a Beast-Warrior and gives 100 ATK. be careful as it can eat up precious Spell/Trap Slots. Phantasm Spiral Crash: Probably the best equip Spell, works when attacking them Directly and can potentially neutralize threats by shifting them to Defense Position. Phantasm Spiral Grip: Gives 500 ATK, really useful to make our Boss Monster actually be able to kill other Boss Monsters head on. Phantasm Spiral Wave: Highly Situational, thats why only 1 copy. Summons Dragon after Battle Phase sadly, but atleast discards 1 card from opponents Hand. Pacifis, the Phantasm City: The best card in the Deck. The entire reason we're playing this. Get this out, if you can protect it you're probably winning. Card of Demise: Really Powerful in the right situations, useless in the wrong ones. Not a must have card, but definitely a strong one. Dark Hole: Board Clears are good for us, we like slow Games because we can get value out of Pacifis. Can destroy our Token in our turn to make room for a new one to trigger Pacifis in their Turn again. Heat Wave: Best card for going first aside from the Field Spell. Stops most Decks from doing anything at all, doesnt annoy us in the slightest. Raigeki: Better Dark Hole aside from clearing our own Token, just an overall good card, if you have it toss it in. Terraforming: Sadly we can't have 3 anymore and that hurt the Deck plenty, always a must have card. Skill Drain: Probably the single strongest card in here aside from Pacifis. If your opponent has no out vs this card they might lose the game on the spot. That's how strong it is. Champion's Vigilance: Deny all when you have the Token or Dragon. 3 feels clunky, 1 feels like not running it at all. Experiment yourself, it's always a good card. Solemn Warning: Just helps with our Gameplan Metaverse: We have to run this Phantasm Spiral Battle: This is the reason why Pacifis is as strong as it is. Searchable  destroy anything that you can play from Hand when Pacifis is on the Board, never run less than 3. Phantasm Spiral Power: Negates Effects, match-up dependent but usually incredibly strong, since it can retrieve Equip Spells from GY you should always run at least 1. Quaking Mirror Force: Most Mirror Forces are good, this one felt the best vs Blue Eyes. Experiment yourself but they're basically just Stun Cards that buy another Turn and potentially set-up your next Turn.   Megalosmasher X: another 4 Star Normal 2000ATK card. We like these, this one is a little special, I'll explain in a bit. Mystic Mine: If you can afford its a good card for going 2nd. Advance Draw: Just a card to think about if you're really budget. Fossil Dig: Only with Megalosmasher X, searches it. Painful Decision: I'd only run if you run 2 sets of 3 copies of Normal Monsters Pot of Extravagance: If you can afford it, use it. Unexpected Dai: A lot of the time basically a Monster card, can sometimes help set-up Extra Deck (yes, you heard correctly) Lose 1 Turn: Really strong stun card, if you can fit it you should probably run it. Sea Stealth Attack: This card almost needs to be in the deck. It can retrieve Pacifis from the GY, protect our Spells/Traps (think Skill Drain) and turns Megalo and our Token into destroyer machines. Sadly doesnt help when Pacifis is banished :( There can only be one: Powerful card but be careful with it because both the Token and our Dragon are Wyrm-Type Fists of the Unrivaled Tenyi: Just a really strong card, experiment with it yourself. Evenly Matched: If you can afford it, its good for 2nd. Storming Mirror Force: Another good Mirror Force Extra Deck: You don't really need one, but there are situations where you're gonna wish that you did indeed get these Utopia/Utopia the Lightning: You need Utopia for Lightning. Lightning gets rid of basically any Boss Monster, its insane. You might not need it vs every Deck, but sometimes it's your only out. Bagooska: If your opponent can't deal with it ( a lot can't ) it buys precious Time for our Deck, really good, but rare to summon. Gem-Knight Pearl: I'll be honest, in over 100 Duels vs Blue Eyes I've summoned this card once, and it almost would have won me the game. Never ever even thought about summoning it vs any other Deck, it might come in handy though. It's cheap so get it if you can, it might save your game one day.   There are a lot more potential cards such as the Paleozoic cards and a few more Extra Deck options, but I personally only found these to be relevant. That's a lot to digest but I hope this gave some overview over the Deck and that it helps you find your own Deck List of Phantasm Spiral. Due to the nature of having the core just be the Field Spell + Cards to search + probably some Normal Monsters the Deck has a decent amount of flexibility. I sincerely hope you have fun with it, your opponents won't :D

Dinosaur combo deck. In some ways it is extremely boring - the main goal is Needlefibre into True King of All Calamities. However, it's also a little bold, in that I've shaken up the True King dino formula a little bit to try and increase consistency, at the cost of interactivity. This is a real cost, and it does lead to the usual problems with super heavy combo decks, especially in a combo format. So, why are you playing Dinos as a going first deck instead of Adamancipator?  One reason is flexibility. Your deck is intrinsically good going second and has easy OTKs (as well as a Borrelsword combo just in case), and the ability to break boards. You also have easy recovery plays in Double Evolution Pill, and while your combos are smaller, that leaves room for more follow-up plays. You won't extend as far as rocks, and you don't get the advantage of Koa'Ki Meiru Guardian, but rocks can also generally be stopped on the Needlefibre, whereas your opponent might not always be able to stop you from using Dinosaur effects at all with Miscellaneousaurus, and that makes it hard to stop Calamities and the Pill at the same time.  I tried to build it with this in mind, so that while you blind going first you're prepared to win going second.  The numbers on Dinosaurs are pretty standard, but there are some meaningful inclusions and exclusions. Lost World is cut - the deck needs a face-lift and Lost World, while an easy consistency boost, doesn't make a whole lot of sense going first. A meaningful inclusion is Carboneddon and Guarddragon Justicia. This can make Coral Dragon of off 6 1 card starters, but more importantly, is also the whole Calamities combo. You don't really care if you see the bricks, since you like having tuners anyways, and Carboneddon is still a Dinosaur monster you can use to activate effects, then get some free value off of.  The extra deck is just layers of combos. The most important is making True King of All Calamities off of Needlefibre, but the extra deck can also make Borrelsword Dragon off of Needlefibre (with the small downside of running Jet Synchron over Deskbot 001, which in turn gives the deck an extra 1 card starter). Since sometimes you have a couple of extra monsters on the field and can't do the combo, we have I:P, with Unicorn and Apollousa being the most notable targets.  Almiraj and Secure Gardna seem weird, but they make Baby dinos with Pill into UTC, and give him fodder. It's just more ways to start plays, so that most combinations of cards will get you onto the field.  I wanted more room for hand traps, but even without Lost World, the Diagram "engine" is still really good in the deck. It doesn't hurt to leave Ravenous Croc or Vermillion Mech on the field when you make Calamities, especially with I:P around, and you just need more ways to pop cards. Gamma seems essential - I need high impact hand traps that are flexible and generic. There's just a lot of stuff only Gamma will answer, and Gamma is generally a better option than other hand traps going second. I don't really care about having bricks in the hand going second, I need the highest impact hardest to interrupt stuff possible. Imperm makes the cut on the other 3 spaces. You could run 7 hand traps, and I think statistically that would be a more correct ratio, but I feel like it's worth seeing hand traps less often to hand them be high impact.  Back on Ash, making space for Deskbot 001. This makes Borrelsword a reliable follow-up and makes Jet Synchron a better starter.  Made space for Gamma. Unsure on the True King Engine, in practice it gives another way to pop cards and opens up value, but it's not strictly necessary most of the time, and you don't see those cards most games. On the other hand, sniping extra decks is cool... But is it as cool as Hand Traps? I think I'll start testing a version without the True King Engine...  Cut Jet Synchron, back to 2 UTC. This freed up space for Carboneddon. Having a back-up way to start combos and a free dino extender is actually pretty useful, you get a lot of value off of Carboneddon. I could just run Jurrac Aeolo #2 and save deck space, but Carboneddon gives me an extra extender, and replaces Jet Synchron as another 1 card Calamities.  Trying a more budget-friendly split of One For One, 1 Animadorned Archosaur, and 1 Jet Synchron. This gives the deck 2 more 1.5 card starters, puts back in the Borrelsword follow-up, saves money, and gives us ways to pitch Carboneddon alongside other fringe benefits (like One For One being a Special Summon, and Archosaur actually being better when special summoned usually.)

deck_excerpt: 5k def, protected, cant be negated, and generates plus directly from deck/extra deck. This is a 3 cards combo but we're running 7 Instant Fusion + 13
deck_description: Oh boy I never expected Syrus Truesdale deck can be taken seriously. This deck is so consistent to spit out Mobile Base protected with Connection Zone. As long as you have the 3 cards mentioned, Instant Fusion + 1 roid + fusion spell, you're good to go. Combo: https://bit.ly/2E8HmUX. I'll explain card by card and their role in deck. The roid (Speedroid): Double Yoyo (for Halq/Accesscode OTK), Terrortop (best roid, free/searcher), 2 Den-Den Daiko Duke (extender for Halq OTK), Taketomborg (extender), 3 Tri-Eyed Dice (best fusion fodder, negates atk from GY). 3 Keeper of Dragon Magic: Instant Fusion/other fusion spell searcher while being Megaroid City fodder. Predap package: 1 Ophrys Scorpio (Instant Fusion/other fusion spell searcher while being Megaroid City fodder), 2 Lonefire, 2 Darlingtonia Cobra (2 just in case its drawn). Fusion spell: Instant Fusion (summons Pair Cycroid for Mobile Base material), 3 Vehicroid Connection Zone (protection and make Mobile Base cant be negated), 1 Poly (Keeper/Ophrys/Verte other target) and 1 Fusion Gate (Set Rotation target). 3 Megaroid City, Set Rotation, and Terraforming: Best card, searches Connection Zone or roid (Speedroid) monster. 1 Emegeroid Call: Negation, also Megaroid City target. The rest is just staple cards. Extra deck: 2 Mobile Base (it can summon its copy from extra deck), Pair Cycroid (combo piece). Jumbo Drill (piercing, for pushing damage), Kitedrake (beater and floats), and Chanbara (4.6k damage output) are all just Mobile Base target. Halq/Selene/Accesscode (OTK), Masq (small resource disruption), Cherubini (sends Daiko Duke for link climb/Halq play), Verte (plan B for fusion spell). Knightmares and Borreload as generic good link monster. Pros: Consistent 5k protected tower that generates plus every turn, can OTK, and big staple slot. Cons: 3 cards combo, Megaroid City locks to fusion for the entire turn. Cards to think of: Fusion Recycling Plant (great field but needs discard, we already have too many discard effect and we dont even need the recovered material, Tri-Eyed Dice is better in GY), Halq combo (summons roid from deck but clashes with Megaroid City, so its preferred to use Halq as OTK instead of going first).
