deck_excerpt: Crimson Nova the Dark Cubic Lord OTK.
deck_description:
The objective is to summon Crimson Nova the Dark Cubic Lord. The easiest way is to get the spell card Cubic Karma into the graveyard. This can be done in a few ways, but Summoner Monk, Duza the Meteor Cubic Vessel, and Foolish Burial Goods will be the main ways. I prefer going second with this deck, so that you can draw that first card and optimize your chance of being able to summon Crimson Nova. Every Cubic spell and trap has a graveyard effect, so using cards like Twin Twisters, Karma Cut, and Darkword Dealings to send any spell/trap cards you have in your hand to the grave is usually the best move.
  • Normal summon Summoner Monk, activate his effect, discard any other spell from your hand (if you can discard Cubic Karma even better), to Special Summon Duza, the Meteor Cubic Vessel from your deck, then use Duza's  ability to send Cubic Karma from your deck to your graveyard. Banish Cubic Karma from your graveyard to add a cubic monster from your deck to your hand - Crimson Nova. Cubic Karma is not once per turn, so if you get multiple in the grave, even better, start stacking your hand.
  • Crimson Nova can be special summoned by revealing any 3 cubic cards from your hand, as long as they have different names.
  • Once Crimson Nova's on the field, you should be able to OTK pretty easily. If Crimson Nova destroys a monster, he's allowed to make a second attack, and you can double his attack with Cubic Wave (as long as your opponent has a face up monster). This ATK increase is permanent too, if you don't OTK. You only need to hit your opponent with 5000 damage too, from there, Crimson Nova's ability with cause the OTK.
  • If you get the the End Phase, Crimson Nova's ability triggers, and each player loses 3000 LP. Performapal Rain Goat protects you from taking damage if you have him in your hand though (just watch for hand traps like Called by the Grave).
Vijam is a great wall in a pinch, too, since he can't be destroyed by battle, if you need an extra turn to set up your hand. I know Dark Garnex, Blade Garoodia, and Buster Gundil are bricks and aren't ideal, but from my play testing, I have never really had an issue with them. You can always swap in any three other cards; but I would still pick Cubic cards if you do, because you really want as many Cubic cards as possible for the best chance to summon Crimson Nova. This deck is obviously not meta in any way, and sometimes it's fun to play it different ways. It's not optimal, but getting out Buster Gundil once and while and having him attack 3 times with 3000 ATK is fun. Not my best or most efficient deck, but it's one of my favorites to play. You can use combinations of Cubic Karma and Cubic Wave to get Crimson Nova's ATK to crazy numbers. Cubic Waves can stack too, so you can double his ATK multiple times. I've even gotten Crimson Nova's ATK over 21,000 ATK once or twice.   Other Options: I've also seen some builds with Monster Gate and Magical Hats to get as many spells/traps into the grave as well; there's lot of room to explore.

So, just a quick summary of all of the card choices.  This is a control deck, meaning you should aim to go first. Your main goal should be to protect your field spell. As long as you can do that, you should be fine. One of the coolest things about Pacifis is the versatility of the deck. Don't be afraid to try different builds.   Monsters Spiral Dragon: 3 is too bricky, 1-2 should be enough. I've seen several decklists that just don't use him at all, but I think he is necessary to close up games a bit quicker. Megalomasher X & Mystery Shell Dragon: The goal here is to have 3-6 normal monsters, of course, other builds would have different rations of monsters. I went with Megalomasher b/c he is a dino (fossil dig), and he can summon Bahamut. Mystery Shell Dragon is a wyrm, meaning we can use him and spiral dragon for tenyi link plays. Plus, both of them have 2000 attack, which is the highest a normal monster can have. Dimension Shifter: A few months ago this was ash blossom. I am not fully sure what the best hand trap would be here, as there are others I want to try, but these slots can go to whatever meta staple fits in your current format. Spells Heat Wave: Can shut down almost every deck, without hurting us one bit. Must have at 3. Fossil Dig: See Megalomasher X Terraforming: We need this because, despite all of the support Umi has, it does not have a searcher. Phantasm Equip Spells: 2 of each except for wave, as we need to wait until the end of the battle phase to special summon a spiral dragon. Thankfully, it can make your opponent discard a card, so it isn't all bad. Pacifis: Your key card, the thing that makes the deck viable. Must have at 3. Traps Metaverse: Since terraforming is limited, we have to run this as well. Phantasm spiral battle & power: Become hand traps when Umi is on the field. Battle is spell speed 2 destruction, while power is an in-archetype infinite impermanence. They also have their second effects, which come up, but are not essential to victory. We don't use trap trick because their appeal is in the fact that you can play them from your hand, and trap trick puts them onto the field. 3 battle and 1 power, but I am considering changing their ratios. Sea Stealth Attack: Can recycle our Pacifis, protect it and our floodgates, while making our spiral dragon and token undefeatable in battle. 3-of. Summon Limit: A floodgate that does nearly nothing to us while ruining our opponent's career. Sure, we cant make as big extra deck plays, but its not like we needed it to win. Gozen Match: Another floodgate, as one can never have too many floodgates. Spiral dragon, ur phantasm tokens and megalomasher X are all water attribute monsters, so this card shouldn't hurt u much. Cant say the same about ur opponent. I am considering bringing it up to 3, but for now its at 2. Skill Drain: The boss of all floodgates, this card can win you the duel on its own.   For the extra deck, you can do whatever you want, or not run an extra deck at all. It's your choice. Note that other builds, the Extra Deck may have a lot more importance in the duel. In general, the only deck that shouldn't be running an extra deck at all is Monarchs. The side deck right now is a mess, filled w/ ideas and speculation. As I perfect the build, the side deck will become clearer. For now though, I would recommend at the very least nibiru, droll, and dark ruler no more. If u have better cards in mind, go for what u thought of, I'm not the best deck-builder in the world. Overall, pretty fun deck to play, maybe not so much for your opponent. But at least it's not mystic mine. All suggestions are welcome and appreciated.

deck_excerpt: Megalith Rituals go brrrrrr and Draitron search goes bzzzzt
deck_description: Draitron is a great engine to combine with the combo Megaliths and since both allow for generic ritual summons you can tech in a few strong ritual monsters to cover your playstyle. Trying to get Dracoverlord out ASAP will net you wins easily, and is very easy to continually ritual summon turn after turn once you get set up. Getting Phul out will start the Megalith combo, and it's pretty easy to get Phul out most of the time. You can use Draitron Nova and summon Al-Zeta for Meteornis Draitron and recycle it while still being able to use it for Phul with the left over 1,000 ATK Draitron. Megaliths quick-play spell Megalith Unformed will let you use a level 8 monster to get to Ophiel which can search and summon Phul. The Cyber Angel Benten engine works amazingly within both archetypes, Megaliths for using tributes to ritual summon and Draitrons for their special summon cost being a tribute. After getting all 3 copies you can then search out Natasha and after ritual summoning her, which is as easy to do with Draitrons as Phul since Natasha only has 1,000 ATK, you can then continually steal monsters while also setting up Link or Xyz monsters. After a while there will be plenty of ritual monsters in the GY to get a nice boost off of Phaleg to beat down anything. If you have the ritual spell Meteornis Draitron but no Draitron monsters out you can use the extra deck Machine monsters, and since they don't have a level they won't count towards the 2 star level requirement on both of the Draitron Ritual monsters. This works especially well if you can get Natasha out and steal a lot of monsters to link out for more ritual fodder. The sidedeck has handtraps if you need them and some tech ritual monsters you can throw in for preference.

deck_excerpt: Geology and Archaeology combine together to create one rocking deck! Budget Fossil Adamancipator Koa'ki Meiru deck running a small Neos engine to faci
deck_description:
This is my first deck posted, hopefully the first of many more to come! :) This deck combines 4 engines together and they work harmoniously together! This deck seeks to control the board with Raptite and Koa'ki Meiru until it can get Fossil monsters out for an OTK. This deck features 17 starters out of 45 cards, so this deck is relatively consistent.
  • Koa'ki Meiru for field control and resources. Destroys themselves to fill graveyard with rock monsters allowing for fossil fusions. Ties of the Brethren allows for summons of 3 Koa'ki Meiru to provide negates and rank 4 plays.
  • Adamancipator increases consistency amongst rock monsters with excavations and provide sychro access to Raptite and more importantly, Dragite.
  • Fossil with their fusion card allows access to powerful fossil fusion monsters by fusing rock monsters in your graveyard along with a monster in your opponents graveyard, kind of like Invocation. Fossil monsters have powerful piercing attacks making OTKs easier to achieve.
  • Neos Fusion to summon Brave Neos to the field sends directly from the deck a level 4 monster as part of it's material, allowing you to send Weathering Soldier to graveyard to search Fossil Fusion.
This deck is meant to be as budget as possible, so expensive cards like Adamancipator Researcher ($50+ USD right now) are taken out. Block Dragon is for free summon and rock monster searches. Nemeses Keystone is for recycling banished rock monsters. Notable cards that can be added to this deck are: Magnet Reverse, Mathmatician, Keeper of Dragon Magic, Rock Bombardment, Gigantes and Tackle Crusader.

deck_excerpt: I threw a bunch of engines into a 60 card deck
deck_description: I really really liked HAT when that was meta. HAT was a deck made of three different self sufficient engines, which meant dead hands were rare. HAT won't work today, but I think the idea could still work well.   ENGINES I chose to work with Evil Eye, Windwitch, Invoked, Dragun, and a small Artifact and Spellbook engine as well. Every single one of these engines can get started with just one card, so even in a 60 card deck you won't dead draw. Running 60 cards also lowers your chances of drawing cards you wouldn't want to normally, such as the normal monsters, scythe, or snow bell. It also gives us plentiful room for hand traps. Evil Eye - IMO this is an underrated engine right now. Drawing either the field spell or Serziel will give you a normal summonable sticky boss monster that has a quick effect removal. It also allows you to search Basillius, which is a free link 2, which opens up Verte Anaconda for Dragun plays. There are 7 cards you could draw (including terraforming) to get this engine going, and drawing any of the other cards isn't a big deal. Invoked - The other main engine of the deck, invoked is a bit less good since you aren't guaranteed to draw a light for Mechaba, but it does give you access to Caliga which is another underrated card IMO. Invoked works much the same as evil eye, as drawing either the field spell or Aleister will get the engine going. Once Aleister is summoned once, the fusion spell with recycle him every turn, making sure you always have a play. Both of these engines rely on the field spell to get started, but neither one particularly cares if it stays on the field, making them easily replaceable with one another. Windwitch - Another 1 card boss monster, Ice bell is a Crystal Wing by itself. Drawing a glass bell can search you the Ice bell for the next turn as well. As a good half of these engines rely on the normal summon, Windwitch is a great addition since it doesn't ever need to normal. Spellbook - This also relies on its normal, but both Blue boy and Secrets gives you a draw 2. If you happen to draw Knowledge on its own, you also run spellcasters in Windwitch, Invoked, and in a pinch Dragun is also a spellcaster. Dragun - Free link 2s means free Red-eyes Fusions. Dragun is a ridiculous boss monster, with the only cost being having to run a few normal monsters. In a 60 card deck, this is less of a problem, and since you can fuse from the deck it's only an upside. Using the spell on its own stops you from summoning for the turn, but if you use Verte Anaconda you can get around this effect. Artifact - Scythe is a crazy card right now. Locking you out of the extra deck is insane. Ideally you never draw scythe and only draw the sanctums, which again is more likely in a 60 card deck. Hand Traps - I'm choosing to run Ash because its Ash, Omega for Numeron, and Ghost Ogre and Nibiru for the light attribute which can also be used to make Mechaba. I did try Infinite Impermanence as well, but I was really missing that light attribute.   Your win condition for this deck can change every game. It's also difficult to side against, since you can do so many different things. I'm not gonna tell you this deck is top tier or even good, but it is fun to pilot and is more consistent than you'd think

deck_excerpt: I hope you enjoy it, every suggestion is welcome
deck_description:
Duelists, i have a problem. Every time i see an archetype with beautiful artworks i try for a long time ways to make it playable (failing miserably most of the time). And that’s exactly what happened when i saw the cards from the new structure deck "Spirit Charmers". This list is the best i could do so far. I'm enjoying the "Performage" package. Hat Tricker is just perfect:  He is EARTH, He is spellcaster, and he is a good extender for rank 4 plays or for "Awakening of the Possessed - Archfiend Reaper of Nefariousness". Speaking of which, we want to summon it from the deck as soon as possible to make a Charmer link monster and search a "possessed" spell/trap. Trick Clown and Damage Juggler can be discarder in different ways (Danger cards, Dark World Dealings, Masters of the Spiritual Arts) and let us to extend our plays. Let’s focus now on some specific cards:
  1. Awakening of the Possessed. We want to have multiple copies on the field. This card let you draw 1 card (hard once per turn unfortunately) but most important makes your monsters BIG (big big).
  2. Bagooska. Best rank 4 monster we have, he let us to do a decent board going first and he doesn't affect our "Charmer" link monsters.
  3. Fairy Tail - Luna. My MVP for this deck with Awakening of the Possessed. She is just so versatile (i'm thinking on building a going second-based deck with kaijus and rainbow neos package, we'll see).
I'm going to try different ways to play this archetype since i still have a couple of months before the release of the structure deck. Sorry for my english, i'm not a native speaker.

deck_name: Legendary Dragon Critias + Lair of Darkness + Trap Trick
deck_excerpt: All Legendary Dragon of Critias together with Lair of Darkness package and a Trap Trick engine with a Waking the Dragon bonus.
deck_description:
It's a versatile and disruptive Casual deck. I love the Legendary Dragons of Critias. Since you run Crush Card Virus in this deck, it's quite obvious that you also run the Lair of Darkness package. Important Notes on the Deck and the Decklist:
  • It's a strict casual deck. No chance here against the meta. But since it's a fun casual deck, it can pull some fun duels and wins off.
  • The sidedeck in this decklist are rather "honorable mentions" cards and not an actual side deck! It's just to keep some different strategies in mind if I'm going to work on this deck again.
Some explanation for certain cards: Waking the Dragon Since you run a lot of traps, your opponent is going to try to pop as many backrow cards as he can. So it's perfect to play Waking the Dragon in this deck. I've the following targets in my extra deck:
  • The Last Warrior from another Planet If your opponent pops Waking the dragon before he controls any monsters, the last warrior will completely shut down your opponent until he has a spell / trap removal.
  • Naturia Exterio If you play against a backrow-heavy deck, this is the ideal target. It can negate any spell / trap, and it's not once per turn! And since this deck doesn't use the graveyard at all, you can banish anything you like, except Darkest Diabolos, Lord of the Lair
  • Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon The counterpart to Naturia Exterio. Great beater with monster-effect negations.
  • Raidraptor - Ultimate Falcon The main beater target. Unaffected by card effects and 3500 ATK.
The possibility that Waking the dragon gets popped more than once is there, so it's good to have multiple targets in your extra deck. Trap Trick I simply love this card. You're able to search out any material for your Legendary Dragon of Critias (except for Tyrant Burst Dragon. But he's not that good and I only have him in the deck is because I like to play all of the dragons...). Another neat combo is, when you have a set Trap Trick, and your opponent activates Harpie's Feather Duster, you can activate it and set a Waking the Dragon, which immediatly get's destroyed. Spirit Reaper Staller (the deck is quite slow) and target for the classic Card Crush Virus. The rest should be self explanatory. I really like this deck, but I know it's not that strong. So if you have any recommendations on how to improve this deck without losing on it's main focus, the dragons, feel free to comment. Oh, and I value fun to play over strength.

deck_excerpt: If "Supay, Duskwalker" had 1500 DEF instead of 1900, this deck would've been even more spicy
deck_description: This Deck is currently built to go first. Basically, you are trying to get out the Sun Dragon Inti and Moon Dragon Quilla loop. Nothing else to say except that there is a Charmer engine using their new cards. Full Combo is "Supay, Duskwalker," "Ascator, Dawnwalker," (with cards for their discards) and Nefarious Archfiend Eater of Nefariousness. "Supay, Duskwalker" and "Ascator, Dawnwalker" Special Summon themselves after you discard a card. Then they Special Summon their respective tuner monsters which are Supay and Fire Ant Ascator. From here, if you have og Archfiend Eater, you can Special Summon him as you control a Spellcaster. Then, you can Special Summon Archfiend Reaper from your deck by tributing a spellcaster and an earth monster. You should really choose to tribute either "Supay, Duskwalker" or "Ascator, Dawnwalker" and Supay or Ascator. Both Supay and Ascator float into something (Ascator summons a level 5 from the grave and Supay summons Oracle of the Sun from Deck). Archfiend Reaper summons back a level 4 monster from the grave which should be the tuner you tributed. Then once you use Reaper for the synchro summon of Inti or Quilla, he can add a Possessed Spell/Trap from your deck. Inti and Quilla summon each other after being destroyed. Possessed Lyna searches "Ascator, Dawnwalker" when shes summoned by her effect. Pot of Extravagance gets you to your combo pieces. The Possessed cards just get you closer to your combo pieces also. Oracle of the Sun really has no purpose here except for being a target for Supay and Ascator. Dimmered Path recycles your "Ascator, Dawnwalker" and "Supay, Duskwalker" for next turn (kinda was just putting in cards to get to 40 cards). Naturia Barkion negates Infinite Impermanence. Red Reign is for that small chance of a 1000 IQ play. Interpret the side deck however you want. I don't see this deck actually winning games. Inca are just the cards used by Rex Goodwin in the anime; there is no real consistency.

deck_excerpt: "Where did that boss monster come from??" "Why are you summoning so much?? It's my turn!!" "How did you wipe my board again??" Welcome to Prank-Kids,
deck_description: Infinite combos and recycling like you would not believe in this deck. You can literally summon either of your boss monsters and board wipe during your opponent's turn without incurring cost thanks to Meow-Meow. It's a 1-card free combo off of any Prank-Kids monster to get a crazy set-up. If you start with any extra resources in your hand (an extra monster, fusion spell, field card, pretty much anything) you can generally combo into both of your boss monsters during your opponent's turn and completely destroy any hope they had of even playing the game.  The ratios I play are pretty standard, the deck just flows like this. I play 3 of the field spell and Terraforming just to bump my odds to 16 cards in my deck that will let me get off my combo. Thunder Dragon Fusion is pretty essential just so there's less fear if I'm forced to banish one of my Prank-Kids off of Rocksies. I saw someone else using The Last Warrior From Another Planet and Cyber-Stein, and I thought it was neat, but not strong enough to include in my main deck, so I've put it in my side just in case I ever want to pull it out, but to be honest, I almost never have to side deck, just because there's not much that can play through this deck (I think I've only ever had to when playing banish-eccentric opponents just to get a second Battle-Butler). If someone can successfully stop the combo early enough, Prank-Kids are done for, but I already play Ash and Called By The Grave at 3 each, and that's about all I've ever really needed.  If I had to change anything, I'd just make space in the side deck for more hand traps and negates, maybe add Infinite Impermanence or Lightning Storm, but realistically, those cards are way too expensive for me anyways.  Always try to go first with this deck just to get your set-up, especially since Meow-Meow can only banish itself during your opponent's turn.  The biggest counter to this deck that I've seen is anything that banishes. Dimension Shifter, Dark Law, Dimensional Fissure, and Macro Cosmos just make me want to die.  If you have any questions about combo tutorials or any ratios that I play, leave a comment down below and I'll try to explain!

deck_excerpt: Control heavy Deck, supposed against lower Tier Meta.
deck_description: Card Informations: Pot of Extravagance: Playing 3x Pot of Extravagance for the only reason of seeing it as often in the start hand as possible, I would never activate it twice in a duel, because the Deck actually needs it's Extradeck. Extradeck is filled with double and triple copies of important cards to decrease the probability to banish everything that you need. PoE is in the end a "gamble" that you may lose sometimes, not often but there's still a certain % to banish everything you need. Always banish 6 for the +2 draw, banishing only 3 is a 1 for 1 exchange with no benefit at all. Also PoE may help sometimes as a bait to get rid of an Ash Blossom, if you already have everything you need to play - just making sure to have an exchange. Numeron Network and Numeron Wall: none of both are Ash'able because Wall doesn't add to hand, it straight up activates and Network sends as cost. If going 1st and able to play the Numeron play just summon 3 Numeron Gates and go into S0 (Nibiru proof play and lockdown for 3 turns). If going 2nd summon 4 Numeron Gates and OTK, this is the only OTK you have in this deck and it actually is pretty viable. You can find online charts for the calculations, in what scenarios you are able to OTK or if your opponent will survive this round. At this point I would just pass on a video, skip to 4:50 to see the chart. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eOg2GYk1f4o Also Numeron Wall can protect you from getting OTK'd. Rikka Xyz: Your main control monster is Teardrop the Rikka Queen, besides S0. Kanzashi the Rikka Queen is decent and if possible should be made after Teardrop, regarding Duelingnexus I have encountered a bug that you can't summon from your opponent GY's as in the replay I wanted to summon BEAWD but couldn't choose it. Terraforming, Mystic Mine and DRNM: Terraforming can be either a Ash bait, enabler for the Numeron play or complete Shutdown by searching Mystic Mine. Having Mystic Mine in the Start hand is basically a free negation bait or a Shutdown for grinding against Combodecks. DRNM is supposed to break boards with Numeron Gates: summon 4 clear whatever you fear and go into S0. Rikka Traps: Decent but not a must have - searchable via Petal and situational super cards, running only 1-1 because they might brick and either way playing enough control overall. Rikka Tranquility is supposed to make an Xyz, may be sided out for something superior if the duels ain't really grind-heavy. 1 Rikka Sheet in Sidedeck because it is actually a good Trap for the reason alone it is searchable. Rikka effects in general: In my replays I have never used an effect to optional tribute a Plant to gain the additional effect, because most of the time it may sound decent but is overall a disadvantage in my opinion. Extra Deck breakdown: Nibiru, Lightning Storm, DRNM, Summon Limit against Combo Decks Lightning Storm, Heavy Storm Duster, Cosmic Cyclone against Backrow heavy Decks. Royal Decree, Red Reboot in addition to the Backrow heavy Decks but specific for Trap heavy decks as Eldlich variants.

Lazy, later.

Oh yeah, it's degeneracy time, baby!   So Altergeist and Guru are two pretty well-known control decks. I think anyone who's been to locals has probably run into one of these decks before, and probably has a few choice words for anyone who plays these decks. So how's about we mash them together and make everyone mad?   The deck can brick, all decks do. But a good hand allows for you to play Guru at first, and then pop off with Altergeist during your opponent's turn. The perfect hand is: The Hidden City, Subterror Guru, Subterror Final Battle, Solemn Judgment, and Altergeist Multifaker. Even if you get Ash Blossomed, you can get Guru on the field with two set back row, and Hidden City. But again, that's a perfect hand. Honestly, you're just looking to play one side of the deck, and drop the other side either during your opponent's turn or right when you're backed into a corner. The side deck is built in a way that should allow you to switch to either Guru Control or Altergeist Control for games 2 and 3.

deck_excerpt: A Deck that aims to use various absurd cards to lock down the opponent on turn one.
deck_description:
Deck Breakdown
  • Deck Type: Stun/Lock
  • Key Cards: Mystic Mine/Spatial Collapse
  • Optimum Opening Hand: Barrier Statue of the Heavens, Ojama Trio/Trap Trick, Ojama Duo/Trap Trick, Spatial Collapse, Rivalry of Warlords.
Since the dawn of time, the occasional anti-fun nut job has come along and sucked all the interactivity out of this game. I aim to do exactly that with this build. We have had champions like Jeff Leonard sneak wins with Mystic Mine, a card of that causes unfathomable groans from anyone who sits opposite it. Regardless, one can not argue with its power, but it needs a little something else. After hours of brewing I come to you with this, this concoction of several stun and forgotten relics of a forgotten era to help end your opponents hopes before they draw their first card. Mind Collapse focuses around a personal favourite of mine; 'Spatial Collapse', a card that restricts both players to having 5 cards max in play at one time. Fill up your opponents field with tokens, slap down a barrier statue or throw up a rivalry and the game is essentially over. Very few decks have the space in the extra to keep utility cards that might be able to remove the tokens being light beast critters, with the only out being Ojama Emperor and who would be running that? Lets not forget Mystic Mine however, a card that is a win condition in and of itself. While it isn't the end of the game if we don't see it, it makes stalling out for our Final Countdown/Cauldron of the Old Man win condition far more manageable.  Impermanence and Ghost Reaper help us going second, as well as disabling any problem monsters that might negate our Mine if it comes to that.  The extra deck is filled with an extravagance board, with the most common outs (light and high use links) filling the spots so we can easily ghost reaper a play starter or extender and limit the ending opponents field. Overall its relatively consistent at setting up some sort of lock turn one (outside the opponent having spell trap removal, which is a standard weakness of these type of decks) but it is in no way competitive and, thanks to our extra deck, is way too expensive. You could easily lower the price by swapping out  the extra deck for any old cards since they will just be banished for extravagance, and by that same token swap out the reapers for Ash Blossom, Nibiru or Dimension Shifter.  Pros
  • Can consistently set up a lock turn one.
  • Has a good match-up against most meta decks.
  • You could make Jeff Leonard proud.
Cons:
  • Dies to MST/Twin Twister etc.
  • Reasonably expensive given its a casual deck (though can be altered).
  • Can get boring.

deck_excerpt: Eldlich control deck with the Solmemn Brigade and Dinomiscus.
deck_description: I like the idea of switching back to Eldlich control right now. A lot of decks are playing combo and are unprepared for the grind game, and IMO, Eldlich control is the best grindgame deck in the game right now, provided you build it for that. People argue Salamangreats can grind further, since they don't have to banish their traps, but Eldlich can overwhelm them with more interaction in the early game, and go for the kill with Trains.  I started with basic Eldlich numbers, 3 Red, 1 White, 3 of each (good) Trap Monster, 3 Lord, 3 Eldland, 1 Countertrap (this will never change till these are hit on the banlist, or new trap monsters are printed). I also think 3 Lost Wind is really core to control builds of Eldlich - they help improve the deck's grind game, and actively want to be binned for Golden Lord or Souls. 3 Souls are the deck's normal summon - why run a brick when you don't have to? These are the main card advantage engine of the deck, and a great combo with Cursed Eldland. The last of the trap suite is slightly spicy.  I knew I wanted to run Dinomiscus this format in control. It's a generic answer to any card that can be targeted, it bins Golden lord, but more importantly, it banishes Golden Lord as well as Block Dragon. The extra effect of summoning a monster to use as material is generically useful as well, and gives the deck access to Eria the Water Charmer Gentle. Solemn Judgement makes a lot of sense. I was considering Compulse or the Trap Hole that banishes, but honestly, you should always run the Solemn cards before those. Judgement and Strike are both cards which uniquely answer a variety cards on generic counter traps, but I chose 3 Judgement and 2 Strike, because the deck already has a lot of monster effect negation, even if it's only on field negation.  I'm running Veiler instead of Gamma because the deck wants to grind out games, and be able to activate hand traps after the first turn while on the board. Gamma felt dead for this slower game plan a lot of the time. Also, this way only Ash Blossom and the Eldlich cards are hard once per turns, meaning seeing multiples of cards is less bad.  Side deck is a bunch of going second cards to break boards and cards to get rid of backrow. I'm very confident in this main going first.

deck_excerpt: A combo Eldlich deck you've never seen before; the "combo" portion of synchron eldlich frails in comparison.
deck_description: Eldlich cards, when thrown into the graveyard, have a search/revive effect. Thus eldlich cards are a great target for danger or lightsworn to be discarded or milled into the grave. Thus, the strategy of this deck is to: 1: summon/special summon lightsworn and danger monsters (or use the effect of spell cards like hand/card destruction and reasoning) to discard/mill eldlich cards, jet synchron, and mecha phantom beast olion into the grave. 2: use the tuners (lightsworn raiden,  jet synchron, mecha phantom) to abuse crystron needlefiber and auroradon to summon A: Blazar or B: Borreload Savage and Herald or C: otk with knightmare unicorn + accesscode talker. The Blazar combo is in this video: https://youtu.be/qb_zKsaAXZw 3: use the search/revive effect of the eldlich cards in the grave to set up eldlich disruptions. The main deck has no hand traps, thus the side deck is filled with handtraps. In the case that a player using this deck is playing a match against a combo deck and he/she knows that his/her opponent is going first, they can side in the handtraps, replacing filler pieces and making this a pure lightsworn eldlich deck with a lot of handtraps. What to side out is the player's choice, but I would suggest keeping the lightsworn engine and the parts of the crucial combo pieces (jet synchron, mecha phantom, deskbot 001) that allows the auroradon combo.

deck_excerpt: Idaten the Conqueror Star is an Isolde by itself and searches Legendary Fisherman. With Isolde and Roland, we search 3 warriors in total making Legend

Important/multi-functional cards are run at maximum copies, such as 3 Red Layer (best starter, Idaten fodder or free monster for Isolde), 3 Vyon (as both Polymerization or high lv warrior for Idaten material thanks to D-Hero Malicious), 3 Polymerization (unbricking the high lv monster for Idaten), 1 RotA (for Vyon or Fire Flint Lady for extender), 3 Durendal (for Fire Flint or Red Layer). 2 Fishermen (as spare if they're used as Idaten material), 2 Overlay Booster (Idaten target for Isolde, 2 for spare if it's used as Idaten material), 1 Kaiki the Unity Star (extender if we have Gearfried, tribute fodder for Fisherman II). The rest are just combo pieces and staples. Pros: Themed, consistent, okay board with followup. Cons: Many high lv bricks.

deck_excerpt: Pure Trickstars 2020 (Updated) (Going First or Second But Wanting to go First)
deck_description: Alright guys, so I know every year I post a Trickstar deck profile for you guys but since there has been banlists and such and its been a while since I posted an updated because of new cards coming out and such, here it is! I have tested this deck, and its crazy good. I hope it can get at least 10k views like my first did. I think it got more than that though. Spread the word to your friends. This deck is really good. Its just a basic Trickstar deck but it really works against the meta, trust me and it hardly bricks. Its a going first build. I want to mention a couple of things you guys might be questioning about my card picks... So first off, the extra deck... ah yes it may be a little confusing at first but Invoked Mechaba is a good Ghost Reaper target PLUS it can be summoned off Cyber Dragon Nova's effect when its sent to the graveyard. This is a countermeasure against Dogmatika! Same with Elder Entity N'tss. A lot of the extra deck is Ghost Reaper targets because in my personal opinion, Ghost Reaper is really strong and slows down most decks or completely kills them. Also I know you see Life Stream Dragon, its a beatstick from Needlefiber's effect! You can summon it from Needlefiber's second effect, tagging out for Life Stream Dragon. I wanted to make good use of Needlefiber and not just have it as a Ghost Reaper target because late game it can come up where you have only handtraps and you can summon 2 ashes for example, in the grind game to make Needlefiber and then during your opponent's turn tag out for Life Stream. And lastly, Trickstar Magical Laurel is good for extending your combos and its searchable via Trickstar Candina. Raigeki in the side deck because of dinosaurs. Hope you guys enjoy and stick around for more! Signing out, MindReader...

deck_excerpt: Deck based on the archetype "Noble Knight" based on the summoning of Xyz and Link monsters, along with a small engine "Infernoble Knight" to send and
deck_description: Deck based on the archetype "Noble Knight" along with a small engine "Infernoble Knight" to send and retrieve from the graveyard our boss monster "Immortal Phoenix Gearfried". As the main base of the deck is the classic "Noble Knight" it focuses on the summoning of Xyz and Link monsters, being the monsters "Artorigus, King of the Noble Knights" and "Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights" being these the owners of moves from the extra deck, being the second a graveyard resource generator to be used by the first in its effects and also help in the invocation and effects of our boss "Immortal Phoenix Gearfried" The summoning engine of our Xyz and Link monsters was based on the combination of the monsters "Noble Knight Gawayn", "Noble Knight Medraut" and "Noble Knight Gwalchavad", the first being the MVP of the deck, since its effect allows us to summon it multiple times in a turn while controlling a normal LIGHT monster being the last two fit to meet this condition as long as they are not equipped with a equip spell card "Noble Arms" will be treated like a normal monster, "Noble Knight Medraut" will allow us to summon to the field any "Noble Knight" from the deck, while the "Noble Knight Gwalchavad" allows us to add from the graveyard to the hand a "Noble Knight" monster. The engine "Infernoble Kinght" has "Foolish Burial" and "Infernoble Kinght Ogier" as the main means to send to the cemetery the "Immortal Phoenix Gearfried", to later add it to the hand with the effects of "Infernoble Arms - Joyeuse" and "Infernoble Knight - Renaud" is the latter being able to retrieve it when specially invoked either by its own effect or with the help of "One for One" and "Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights", this will allow us to generate resources in our graveyard in the form of equip spell cards "Noble Arms" to use in the effects of our Xyz monsters "Artorigus, King of the Noble Knights" or "Sacred Noble Knight of King Artorigus" which can equip them from the graveyard when invoked, helping in turn in the recovery (through "Infernoble Arms - Joyeuse") and invocation of "Immortal Phoenix Gearfried". We also have a recycling and Draw engine made up of the monsters "Noble Knight Brothers" and "Infernoble Knight Maugis", the first helps us in summoning other monsters "Noble Knight" from our hand, and also allows us to add from our graveyard to the deck a combination of 3 "Noble Knight" monster cards or "Noble Arms" cards, while the second allows us to add to the deck a combination of 3 FIRE monster cards or equip spell cards that are in our graveyard or banished, also offers protection against battle destruction by being able to equip from the graveyard a warrior monster on the field, both allow us to draw a card from the deck when we use recycling effect. - Deck construction explanation - Under Construccion - Combos - Combo (1): Medraut + Noble Arms (No Joyeuse or Excalibrun) + Gawayn. 1) Normal Summon: "Noble Knight Medraut", we equip it with a equip spell card "Noble Arms" 2) Effect of "Medraut" we special summoning the "Noble Knight Gwalchavad" from the Deck, we destroy our "Noble Weapons" as part of the effect. Note: If the card "Noble Arms" were "Noble Arms - Arfeudutyr" or "Noble Arms - Caliburn" we can use its effect to destroy a set card or gain life respectively, before activating the effect of "Medraut". 3) Effect of the "Noble Arms" these are equipped from the cemetery to "Gwalchavad". 4) As long as we control a Normal LIGHT monster ("Medraut") we will be able to special summon the "Noble Knight Gawayn" from our hand. Note: Perform this happened multiple times if we have more than one copy of "Gawayn" in hand. 5) We performed the link summon of "Isolde, Two Stories of the Noble Knight" using "Medraut" and "Gawayn" as materials; Effect (1) of "Isolde" we search  and added a warrior monster from our deck to the hand. 6) Effect of "Gwalchavad" We added to our hand "Gawayn" from our cemetery, we destroyed our "Noble Arms" as part of the effect. Note: If the card "Noble Arms" were "Arfeudutyr" or "Caliburn" we can use its effect to destroy a set card or gain life respectively, before activating the effect of "Gwalchavad". 7) Effect (2) of "Isolde": We send from our deck to the graveyard 4 equip spell cards (at least one of them must be "Infernoble Arms - Joyeuse") to special summon the "Infernoble Knight Ogier" from our deck. 8) Effect (1) of "Ogier": We sent "Immortal Phoenix Gearfried" from our deck to the graveyard. 9) We performed the link summon of "Bujinki Ahashima" using "Gwalchavad" and "Ogier" as materials. 10) effect (1) of "Ahashima": We special summon "Gawayn" from our hand and from the cemetery to "Gwalchavad", we perform the Xyz summon of "Artorigus, Noble Knight King" using both as materials. 11) Effect (1) of "Artorigus": When is Xyz summon we can equip up to 3 equip spell cards "Noble Arms" from our graveyard (at least one of them must be "Joyeuse"). Note: If the other "Noble Arms" cards were "Arfeudutyr" or "Caliburn" we can use their effect to destroy a set card or gain life respectively. 12) Effect (1) of "Joyeuse": We add to our hand "Gearfried" from our graveyard, "Joyeuse" is destroyed as part of the effect. Note: If our opponent still has magic or trap cards we can activate the effect of "Artorigus" to destroy up to 3 magic or trap cards on the field. 13) Effect (1) of "Gearfried": We banished "Joyeuse" from our graveyard to special summon him from our hand. 14) Effect (2) of "Ogier": From our cemetery we equip this card to "Gearfried" in the field.

deck_excerpt: A Fusion focussed-deck which uses "Fluffal" and "Edge Imp" monsters for card draw, searches and overall consistency and "Frightfurs" for various destr
deck_description:
This is my take at a "Fluffal"/"Frightfur" deck. The group of archetypes consisting of "Fluffals", "Edge Imps" and "Frightfurs" work in unison to create a strong, consistent and OTK-able Fusion deck with various combos and approaches regarding gameplay, and its overall interactivity explains why the deck is so widely popular.

The Main Deck is all about fetching the right cards to allow for multiple Fusion summons and to build a board that can clear the way and go for the face. To reach such a goal, we have a number of solid cards to work with. "Fluffal Dog" is one of your various searchers and fetches other "Fluffals" and "Edge Imp Sabres" upon being summoned from the hand, which can be easily combined with "Fluffal Penguin", which allows for the Special Summon of another "Fluffal" from the hand. "Fluffal Penguin" is also very useful as Fusion material, since it allows you to draw two cards and discard one when used for a Fusion, which is a definite plus and potential setup depending on what you discarded. "Fluffal Owl" is a searchable searcher for "Polymerization" as well as having a Fusion effect on it own, while "Fluffal Cat" can reuse "Polymerization" when it is used as Fusion material. Both "Fluffal Owl" and "Fluffal Cat" are only at one, since they are searchable and not really necessary at higher numbers. I also added one copy of "Fluffal Angel" for testing purposes, which mostly comes into play as a Spell card that can revive monsters, but is more searchable than other options the deck would have at its disposal (with "Suture Rebirth" being unsearchable and "Frightfur Reborn" only being able to revive the wrong cards most of the time; both of those are not in the deck for said reasons).

One cannot talk about "Fluffals" without mentioning "Toy Vendor". This card does pretty much everything, from card draw and searches to setup and summoning. For this reason, there are also a few cards in the deck that can interact with the three copies of "Toy Vendor": "Fluffal Bear" can be discarded to search for them, "Fluffal Dolphin" can fetch them back from the graveyard while also having a very useful "Foolish Burial" effect alongside that and "Fluffal Wings" can destroy it for a draw two effect with an added search, meaning a major plus in card economy.

On the "Edge Imp" side of things, I am running one copy of "Edge Imp Sabres", since it is easily searchable via the plethora of effects at your disposal while also featuring its own revive effect (which can also be used to setup "Toy Vendor's" summon effect), "Edge Imp Chain" is at three since it searches for cards and the newer "Edge Imp Scythe" is also featured at three copies for the ability of Fusion summoning monsters as a Quick Effect during the opposing turn without the need of using a Fusion Spell.

The Spell line-up is pretty standard for a "Fluffal"/"Frightfur" deck: Three "Polymerization" are absolutely paramount since you will Fusion summon a lot and can search for it in your own archetype, three "Toy Vendor" are there for all manner of effects and interactions, three copies of "Frightfur Patchwork" for being a straight +1 as a searcher, three "Foolish Burial Goods" mainly to send "Toy Vendor" directly to the graveyard to trigger its search effect and both one copy of "Frightfur Fusion" for "Frightfur Tiger" and "Frightfur Wolf" shenanigans and one copy of "Frightfur Repair" mostly for the secondary effect that allows you to summon additional monsters from the hand. The last three slots I filled with one "Foolish Burial" to ditch either "Edge Imp Sabres" or "Fluffal Wings", one copy of "Twin Twisters" for easy backrow removal and to possibility to destroy my own "Toy Vendor" alongside some opposing backrow to profit from the search and one copy of "Super Polymerization" to go into "Starving Venom Fusion Dragon", which not only is a nice fit for a "Frightfur" deck due to its effects but also gets rid of opposing monsters in the process. These last three choices are absolutely debatable, but I tend to keep my decks fairly budget-friendly and the copies of "Infinite Impermanence" and "Forbidden Droplet" that are currently found in other "Fluffal"/"Frightfur" decks are fairly expensive.

The Extra Deck is also pretty straightforward: "Frightfur Cruel Whale" is all the rage right now, and for good reason since it offers destruction, setup and ATK boosts in one fell swoop. "Frightfur Kraken" allows for non-destruction removal and multiple attacks, "Dangerous Frightfur Nightmary" can grow into a sizeable beater while bringing her own setup and protection, "Frightfur Tiger" clears the way and buffs your monsters while "Frightfur Wolf" potentially attacks for 5+ times; "Frightfur Sheep" is probably the least useful member, but has its merit in certain matchups. On the more generic side, I run one "Bahamut Shark" (easily summonable via "Fluffal Penguin" and the added summon of a "Fluffal Dolphin") to summon "Toadally Awesome" and steal opposing cards. The "Cross Sheep" is there for even more insanity with the right board, since it allows for the resummon of "Fluffal Penguin" or other monsters which can use their effects multiple times per turn if they leave the field in some way.

My list is actually pretty similar to various other "Fluffal"/"Frightfur" lists, but after reading through the archetype you will automatically find certain ratios and cards to be desireable, which is why so many people come up with similar lists and results when it comes to "Fluffals" and "Frightfurs".

If you want to know more about the archetype in general and maybe take a look at an analysis that features all the cards the three archetypes have on offer, feel free to visit my archetype analysis for "Fluffals", "Edge Imps" and "Frightfurs" on my blog under this link: https://cubiccreativity.wordpress.com/2020/08/30/archetype-analysis-fluffal-edge-imp-frightfur/.

deck_excerpt: Crimson Nova OTK Deck (Legacy of the Duelist)
deck_description:
This deck was built in mind for Legacy of the Duelist, so I limited myself to only that card pool. The objective is to summon Crimson Nova the Dark Cubic Lord. The easiest way is to get the spell card Cubic Karma into the graveyard. This can be done in a few ways, but Summoner Monk, Duza the Meteor Cubic Vessel, and Foolish Burial Goods will be the main ways. I prefer going second with this deck, so that you can draw that first card and optimize your chance of being able to summon Crimson Nova, and to make use of things like Lightning Storm (and Evenly Match, but I put that in the Side Deck). Every Cubic spell and trap has a graveyard effect, so using cards like Twin Twisters, Karma Cut, and Darkword Dealings to send any spell/trap cards you have in your hand to the grave is usually the best move.
  • Normal summon Summoner Monk, activate his effect, discard any other spell from your hand (if you can discard Cubic Karma even better), to Special Summon Duza, the Meteor Cubic Vessel from your deck, then use Duza's  ability to send Cubic Karma from your deck to your graveyard. Banish Cubic Karma from your graveyard to add a cubic monster from your deck to your hand - Crimson Nova. Cubic Karma is not once per turn, so if you get multiple in the grave, even better, start stacking your hand.
  • Crimson Nova can be special summoned by revealing any 3 cubic cards from your hand, as long as they have different names.
  • Once Crimson Nova's on the field, you should be able to OTK pretty easily. If Crimson Nova destroys a monster, he's allowed to make a second attack, and you can double his attack with Cubic Wave (as long as your opponent has a face up monster). This ATK increase is permanent too, if you don't OTK.
  • You only need to hit your opponent with 5000 damage too, from there, Crimson Nova's ability with cause the OTK. If you get the the End Phase, Crimson Nova's ability triggers, and each player loses 3000 LP. Performapal Rain Goat protects you from taking damage if you have him in your hand though (just watch for hand traps like Called by the Grave).
Vijam is a great wall in a pinch, too, since he can't be destroyed by battle, if you need an extra turn to set up your hand. I know Geira Guile, Blade Garoodia, and Buster Gundil are bricks and aren't ideal, but from my play testing, I have never really had an issue with them. You can always swap in any three other cards; but I would still pick Cubic cards if you do, because you really want as many Cubic cards as possible for the best chance to summon Crimson Nova. This deck is obviously not meta in any way, and sometimes it's fun to play it different ways. It's not optimal, but getting out Buster Gundil once and while and having him attack 3 times with 3000 ATK is fun. In this deck, you're always looking for ways to burn your opponent (Crimson Nova's effect mainly), but Geira Guile, Gagaga Cowboy, Gustav Max, and Blackship of Corn are all there to help boost that burn damage for an OTK. Not my best or most efficient deck, but it's one of my favorites to play. You can use combinations of Cubic Karma and Cubic Wave to get Crimson Nova's ATK to crazy numbers. Cubic Waves can stack too, so you can double his ATK multiple times. I've even gotten Crimson Nova over 21,000 ATK once or twice.   Other Options: I've also seen some builds with Monster Gate and Magical Hats to get as many spells/traps into the grave as well; I've tried those, but I didn't prefer them. I've also tried some Barrel Behind the Door builds where you send Crimson Nova's effect damage that you receive back at your opponent, but it wasn't very consistent. There's lots of room to explore.

deck_excerpt: All about using dice and manipulating them for big effects.
deck_description: All about using dice and manipulating them for big effects.
The goal is to repeatedly use the two virus cards in the deck to destroy your opponents deck.

Control version of Valkyrie. Card Choices: World Legacy Succession, World Legacy's Secret, Lib the World Key Blademaster
  • Allows a searchable "Reborn" like card(s)
  • A way to out Dragoons without targeting or destroying.
  • World Legacy's Secret is a continuous trap for the summon of Valkyrie Sigrun.
Valkyrie monster ratios
  • 2 Valkyrie Sigrun & 2 Valkyrie Sechste for consistency purposes. Lowers the rate of drawing Valkyrie monsters without a reborn/special summon spell
  • 1 Valkyrie Dritte due to 3 Condemned Witch, which can tutor out Valkyrie Dritte during the opponent's turn.
  • 1 Valkyrie Vierte due to the excavation effect and the floating effect. It can be special summoned through Valkyrie Sechste and Valkyrie Sigrun or searched by Valkyrie Dritte
  • 1 Valkyrie Erda due to her being the main brick of the deck.
  • 1 Valkyrie Zweite due to the stats of the monster. Though it can out a monster, it does target.
  • No Ride of the Valkyries or Mischief of the Time Goddess due to ratios of Valkyrie monsters as well as the stats of the monsters. Also the constraint of only controlling Valkyrie monsters would make the deck more of a glass cannon.
Notable Combos/synergies:
  • Valkyrie Erda + Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit:
    • Valkyrie Erda's effect when its special summoned by the effect of a Valkyrie monster banishes anything destroyed by battle or card effect.
    • Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit's effect destroys a card, that was already face up on the field, that activates its effect.
    • With Valkyrie Erda on the field when summoned by the effect of a Valkyrie monster, any card that Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit destroys with its effect is banish instead.
  • Condemned Witch + Celestial Transformation:
    • Normal summon Condemned Witch and search Forbidden Droplet. Set both Droplet and Celestial Transformation.
    • During the opponent's turn, tribute Condemned Witch to special summon a level 4 Light Fairy, Valkyrie Dritte. Valkyrie Dritte's effect to search out Valkyrie Sechste.
    • You can use Celestial transformation to special summon out the Valkyrie Sechste to summon out Valkyrie Erda from your deck.
    • Forbidden Droplet can use Valkyrie Sechste as a viable tribute since it will be destroyed anyways due to  Celestial Transformation's condition.
    • This combo can also be used to special summon Valkyrie Sigrun with Valkyrie Sechste's effect you have Valkyrie Erda in your hand.
  • Valkyrie Sechste + World Legacy Succession
    • Normal summon Sechste and link into Linkuriboh (or Salamangreat Almiraj).
    • Activate World Legacy Succession to special summon back the Valkyrie Sechste triggering its effect to summon out Valkyrie Erda from the deck.
    • Link Sechste and Linkuriboh (or Salamangreat Almiraj) for Lib the World Key Blademaster. Lib's effect can set World Legacy's Secret.
    • This combo can also be used to special summon Valkyrie Sigrun with Valkyrie Sechste's effect you have Valkyrie Erda in your hand.
  The deck is built to main go first, with cards such as Condemned Witch and a more trap orientated build.

deck_excerpt: A semi-competitive Tenyi Deck (Complete w/ Side)
deck_description: The basic idea of this deck is to get out your Tenyi Extra Deck monsters and other supports to disrupt your opponent (kinda) and have the biggest, baddest monsters. While certainly not Meta worthy, I hope it may be able to compete in that area, as I've put qite a lot of thought and research into this deck.  Basically, if you have the ability to, you want to get out Shaman of the Tenyi with Mare Mare in the grave so that you can get Sahasrara with Mare and a Mini-Mare. If you go second, you can get a Spirit Token, and therefore a Berserker by way of Linkuriboh, ending up with 2 monsters with 3000 ATK. Mystic Mine is in there to stall, and Cynet Storm is there, 'cause a) why not? and b) works with Set Rotation. Notice some cards can be bricks... hence the Side Deck. Note also that if you incorporate some of the Side Deck, you can get White Aura Bihumat (on your opponent's turn, no less). Here's how:  Step 1: Get Halqifibrax (should be easy enough)  Step 2: Use it's effect and get Jet Synchron and use to get Linkuriboh  Step 3: Summon Jet from the Grave, use Linkuriboh and Jet to get Dagda  Step 4: Use Dagda to set Scythe  Step 5: On opponent's turn, banish Halqifibrax for Wonder Magician  Step 6: Destroy Scythe using Wonder Magician's effect, then use Scythe and Wonder Magician to get Bihamut  Congradulations! Your mind has been broken (btw this was taken from a somewhat popular article by baMMax. Giving credit where it's due).

The objective is to summon Union Carrier with the Simorghs, then you summon them back from the graveyard and make Simorgh, Bird of Sovreignty.  Use Union Carrier to equip Mist Valley Thunderbird to Simorgh, during the end phase summon Ape Avian from the had or deck with Simorgh. Proceed to negate a lot of stuff. Otherwise summon the barrier statue if you think you'll need it more.  With simorgh onslaught, you can get the birds in your hand and in your graveyard. You can either normal summon them (you get extra normal summons with bird of the beginning and the field card) or you can try to get them in the graveyard to use their special summoning effect.  The synchros and xyzs are there for when things go wrong and you either need more cards or to destroy your opponent's stuff. Nahata and unexpected dai help getting them out.  If you manage to succesfully lock your opponent out of his turn you can use borreload, and S39 to finish your opponent, if you need to stall longer summon what's left between Dark Simorgh, the barrier statue and Apex avian.  Possible cheap additions to this deck are anti spell fragrance to combo with Dark Simorgh or Harpie's Feather Storm.

deck_excerpt: Public secret of Buster Blader deck is to have 1 dragon in GY and Prologue access. We run 9 Prologue and dragon link engine easily fulfill the materia
deck_description: No Linkross, no Elpy, it means we only use minimal dragon link combo. We turbo Romulus via Striker Dragon like usual, add Boot Sector Launch and Ravine, use Ravine discard 1 (Memories should be the discard priority if drawn, Dragon Buster comes next) send Absorouter, use Absorouter add Tracer, use Boot Sector ss Tracer, use Tracer pops field ss Synchron, make Pisty on the left zone, then make Striker Dragon again like standard, use Pisty ss 1 dragon, make Borrelend. Set Prologue/Trap Trick to complete the combo. We can have Dragon Buster lock by sending it with Prologue from deck or Ravine from hand if we already guaranteed to have Memories in GY.  The main deck is mainly consist of extender to support normal summoned Buster Whelp for dragon link. REDMD, Noctovision, Monster Reborn, Quick Launch, and World Legacy Guardragon are the perfect choice for it. Only 2 Black Metal Dragon cus its not our main normal summon but its still a 1 card dragon link (but we have to hard draw Prologue/Trap Trick). The rest is just staples.  Pros: Super consistent, big monsters, floodgate effect, many staples.  Cons: Bad matchup against backrow deck, link monster cant be in def position.

deck_description: This is actual Aromages; pure Aromages. Lonefire Blossom into Evil Thorn into two other Evil Thorns into Aromaseraphy Jasmine. Gain LP to use Jasmine to search Laurel, your free special summon. He can be bumped up or down as you wish. Special summon him to a zone she points to, then tribute him off for whatever you like. Talaya protects from destruction by card effects, Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram protects from targeting, Aromaseraphy Jasmine protects from battle, normal Marjoram protects from taking damage. simple enough. No it's not going to be putting up insane boards turn one, but if you draw right and grind, you can make your plant waifus nearly untouchable.     In case the game gets simplified to unga bunga big number go bonk, Ancient Sacred Wyvern can help. If your opponent likes special summoning from hand, slap them with a 1000 LP tax on it with Queen of Thorns. Cauldron is just to help with LP, but in case you go up against Mystic Mine and you have it, tell them to f*** off by playing it and watching them burn. Remember to chain block; all the Aromage effects will activate at the same time and are mandatory, though a lot of them are soft once per turn. Homemade and fun, enjoy the deck from the Mommy Marjoram to the basically free recycling of plants from the grave.

An Adamancipator deck that looks to lock down the game turn 1 or 2 through Dragoon and a multitude of negates.

With the help of your Adamancipator engine, you will excavate your deck quickly, digging up and summoning your fossil fusions/rock monsters and do big damage to your opponent! So far this deck has been a lot of fun playing against my friends (and long time Yu-Gi-Oh! enthusiasts) during our evening, "Duels @ Dusk!". I think the strategy is pretty self-explanatory when looking at the provided deck list. Not sure if it would be considered meta, but, even without the use of a side deck, I'm 12-0 against ALL of my friend's and their best decks. Please, feel free to drop some knowledge, as I am somewhat new to the current game as it stands! I like to chat about possible strategies! UPDATE: Added a few extra tech monsters/spells to the deck for a few different options. Each variation of the deck performed almost entirely the same way (obviously), unless the effect of the new tech was introduced. 15-1 as of this evening 9/5/2020 UPDATE: Played a couple games last night with an extra Mathematician. The three Mathematician actually helped the flow of the strategy. This is the best build I've had luck with so far using an almost pure Earth/rock theme to summon Fossils! 9/6/2020 UPDATE: The deck felt cluttered this evening and after adding so many different tech cards, it felt as if they were only slowing down the main focus: find Fossil Fusions and summon from the extra deck. I ended up removing a lot of the fodder cards and settled on more direct approach. relying on the Adamancipator engine to excavate those lower level cards that help my strategy more, rather than trying to negate the opponent at every turn. This build feels much faster (removing cards such as Gate Blocker, Tackle Crusader and the third Block Dragon) although, I think the single Primineral Kongreat will be swapped out for the full playset of Block Dragons. Even though I like the idea of the card itself (Primineral), I rarely use it's effect, as it is very easily avoidable. 9/12/20 UPDATE: Bye-bye Block Dragon 9/13/2020

deck_excerpt: Yu-gi-oh TCG Empowered World Chalice combo deck
deck_description: I was surprised to see that the Field Spell Empowerement isn't a hard once per turn. So you can special summon with it multiple times within one turn if you run multiple copies or bounce it back to your hand with cards like Blackwing Zephyros the Elite. I chose World Chalice to go with the Empowered engine since it's a combo heavy deck and somewhat focuses on Normal Monsters that the Empowered have some synergy with. Mainly Beckoned by World Chalice since it's a Warrior and can therefore bring out Isolde which is a great combo maker. The deck can make some pretty crazy combos but isn't as consistent as some more "mainstream" combo decks. It has a lot of bricks like the bamboo cards and 3 normal monsters. Never the less the deck is really fun to use. I often ended up making misplays because I got overwhealmed by the possible ways I can end the combos. Replays: https://youtu.be/ZQo4DVJkswg

deck_excerpt: The Evil Twins in Traditional Format.
deck_description: The Live Twins that were recently released may be somewhat underwhelming in the real game with at best being a mediocre rank-4 fiend engine, but when I had been thinking about it, if Knightmare Mermaid was still legal, they'd have truly shone. deck_excerpt: A synchron based deck that uses junk speeder to turbo a strong synchro each turn
deck_description: So the basic combo is summon Junk Speeder *NOTE WHENEVER SUMMONING SPEEDER SUMMON IT TO THE EMZ IF POSSIBLE* speeder eff to summon as many cards as possible. If  you could summon road synchron off of speeder's effect (it isn't chilling in your hand), use satellite synchron, junk synchron, and road synchron with speeder to summon red supernova dragon If road synchron is chilling in your hand while you use speeder's effect then synchro stardust charge warrior using a jet synchron and speeder. Then summon jet synchron from grave and use jet synchron, satellite synchron, junk synchron, and stardust charge warrior to summon supernova. Those are the easiest ways to summon the big boi supernova The optimal way to summon speeder is with junk converter to discard a tuner, add junk synchron, summon junk synchron, bring back converter, summon speeder, speeder cl 1 converter cl 2 converter special junk synchron from grave The best possible starting combo is converter, a tuner, and a doppelwarrior (this is going to take some time to walk through so you might want to skip this if you don't care) (this works if you can put doppelwarior and speeder on the board in any way) Converter ef to discard it and the tuner and search junk synchron Junk synchron eff when summoned to special converter Use doppelwarrior ef here to special from hand Synchro junk speeder with converter and junk synchron Speeder cl 1 (special a satellite synchron, road synchron, and jet synchron) Converter cl 2 (special junk synchron) Synchro supernova with road synchron, junk synchron, satellite synchron, and speeder Synchro marcher with doppelwarrior and the jet synchron Doppelwarior cl 1 Martial Metal Marcher cl 2 (special junk synchron) *NOTE EITHER MARCHER OR SUPERNOVA MUST BE IN THE EMZ RIGHT NOW* Jet synchron eff to special itself from grave Synchro Celestial Double Star Shaman with a token and jet synchron Shaman effect summon doppelwarior Synchro T.G. Hyper Librarian with the token, doppelwarior, and shaman Doppelwarrior effect Synchro Herald of the Arc Light with junk synchron and a token Synchro Cosmic Blazar Dragon with herald, marcher, and librarian   Yes I did just write an essay to explain how to put an omninegate and a boardwipe on the board, I am sorry   Explanation of some weird cards - Dark World Dealings  - once upon a time (in MR 4) these where quickdraw synchrons, but now quickdraw just clogs up my board and only helps with a discard, dealings also draws though which helps a lot - noodlefiber (Cryston Halqifibrax) - If you hard brick or get into a grindy game it can help - Synchro Chase - Synchro chase + speeder access lets you go into crystal wing and supernova turn 1 also lets you get out of some bad situations I dont like it as much though - Cyberse Gadget - good to go into speeder, also leaves behind a token so makes it possible to easily summon more synchros after the speeder effect - Tuningware - VERY good One for One target, especially if u can't summon speeder otherwise - Dotscraper - same as tuningware except VERY good discard fodder too - Pot of Avarice - why only 2? Because oppening it turn 1 is a brick, you only need it in a grindy game - Why the side deck? - I just added some funny cards and then some decent cards - Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit- Why tf are you playing 1 hand trap and ghost ogre at that? - it is a good summon off needlefiber in the grindy games especially if you are only going into needlefiber to summon formula synchron for blazar on their turn - Synchron Carrier - allows you to play through a hand trap - Satellite Warior - the only removal bar supernova that this deck has, easy to summmon off of speeder, just summon  jet synchron and satellite, synchro stardust charge with speeder and jet synchron, synchro satellite synchron, synchro satellite warrior with stardust charge and satellite synchron - Scarred Warrior - A generic lv 5 for blazar or stepping up in synchros, works with synchro chase and satellite synchron so is also good with that HALP IM GOING SECOND OR GOT HAND TRAPPED!! - GG - This deck struggles to play through even 1 negate wo called by the grave, you need to have a good way to bait it out, if you are going second probably fix the side deck with cards like lightning storm or something
